{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780204866754,"sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","part":{"id":"prt_e7c7a8cc0001iH0qSCyRes00lu","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"7f8cc547ebf14c9c334717b34a2bd9f13f54100d","messageID":"msg_e7c7a7fe2001ZCmSLAWtM5W1Nq","sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":25453,"input":428,"output":144,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":1136,"read":23745}},"cost":0.0024531}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780204869109,"sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","part":{"id":"prt_e7c7a95f2001SaWI6yvwGdej6m","messageID":"msg_e7c7a8dac001fYFQWMEsKOY24Q","sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","snapshot":"eb5d45e14310a4243f3a26ca1acc7b63f6667457","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780204870159,"sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_d2nwfgn6x5o0_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_md_template.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_md_template.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: SKILL.md File Templates - Creation Guide\n3: description: Templates and guidelines for creating effective SKILL.md files for AI agent skills with complete scaffolds and section guidance.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # SKILL.md File Templates - Creation Guide\n7: \n8: Templates for creating SKILL.md files with proper structure, frontmatter, and required sections.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n13: \n14: ### Purpose of SKILL.md Files\n15: \n16: SKILL.md files define AI agent skills - reusable capabilities that extend an agent's functionality for specific domains or workflows. A well-crafted SKILL.md:\n17: \n18: - **Triggers automatically** when relevant patterns are detected\n19: - **Guides the agent** through specialized workflows\n20: - **Maintains consistency** across conversations\n21: - **Encodes expertise** in specific domains\n22: \n23: ### Template Overview\n24: \n25: This guide provides **one comprehensive SKILL template** (Section 3) that covers all skill types from simple single-purpose tools to complex multi-mode orchestrators.\n26: \n27: **The template is flexible:**\n28: - **Simple skills**: Use required core sections only (WHEN TO USE, SMART ROUTING, HOW IT WORKS, RULES, REFERENCES)\n29: - **Skills with bundled resources**: Include detection context, merged resource domains/mapping, loading levels, and one authoritative Smart Router Pseudocode block; use `references/`, `assets/`, and `scripts/`\n30: - **Multi-mode skills**: Expand WHEN TO USE and HOW IT WORKS sections by mode\n31: - **All skills**: MUST include Section 2 (SMART ROUTING) with detection guidance + domain-based routing + pseudocode\n32: \n33: **Target size**: 800-2000 lines for SKILL.md (<5k words total)\n34: \n35: **Examples**:\n36: - Simple: Unit test generator, documentation formatter (no bundled resources)\n37: - Moderate: API client, specialized code reviewer (with references and assets)\n38: - Complex: Workflow orchestrator, document quality pipeline (multi-mode with extensive resources)\n39: \n40: ### Progressive Disclosure Principle\n41: \n42: SKILL.md architecture follows progressive disclosure:\n43: \n44: 1. **Metadata** (YAML frontmatter) - Always in context (~100 words)\n45: 2. **SKILL.md body** - When skill activates (<5k words)\n46: 3. **Bundled resources** - Loaded as needed (unlimited size)\n47: \n48: **Critical**: Keep SKILL.md <5k words. Move detailed content to `references/`, `scripts/`, or `assets/`.\n49: \n50: ### Document Type Requirements\n51: \n52: **Enforcement Level**: STRICT (SKILL.md files require perfect structure)\n53: \n54: **Required Elements**:\n55: - ✅ YAML frontmatter with required fields\n56: - ✅ H1 title with subtitle\n57: - ✅ Numbered H2 sections (ALL CAPS)\n58: - ✅ Section separators (`---`)\n59: - ✅ No table of contents (forbidden in SKILL.md)\n60: \n61: **Quality Targets**:\n62: - Structure: 100/100\n63: - Content quality: High (AI-evaluated)\n64: - Overall: High (human/AI judgment)\n65: \n66: ---\n67: \n68: ## 2. FRONTMATTER REQUIREMENTS\n69: \n70: ### Required Fields\n71: \n72: | Field | Required | Format | Example |\n73: |-------|----------|--------|---------|\n74: | `name` | ✅ | hyphen-case | `my-skill-name` |\n75: | `description` | ✅ | Single line, **≤ 130 chars** for skills (≤ 110 for commands); 1,536-char hard cap | `\"Handles X when Y occurs\"` |\n76: | `allowed-tools` | ✅ | Array: `[Tool1, Tool2]` | `[Read, Write, Edit, Bash]` |\n77: | `version` | ⭐ | Semver | `1.0.0` |\n78: \n79: > **Description budget & trim style**: see [`frontmatter_templates.md` § Description Budget & Trim Style](../frontmatter_templates.md). Total project descriptions must stay under ~5,600 chars or Claude Code will silently drop the longest from auto-discovery. Authoring rules: drop product/stack enumerations, drop marketing prose; keep skill name, primary verb, domain noun, and mode suffixes (`:auto`/`:confirm`).\n80: \n81: ### Template\n82: \n83: ```yaml\n84: ---\n85: name: sk-example\n86: description: Example workflow skill demonstrating proper frontmatter format with specific capabilities, use cases, and key differentiators for AI agent discovery.\n87: allowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]\n88: version: 1.0.0\n89: ---\n90: ```\n91: \n92: ### Key Rules\n93: \n94: - **name**: Must match folder name exactly, hyphen-case only\n95: - **description**: Third-person voice, single line, no `<>` brackets\n96: - **allowed-tools**: Use brackets `[...]`, not comma-separated string\n97: \n98: > **Complete Reference**: For validation rules, edge cases, array formats, and all document type frontmatter, see [frontmatter_templates.md](frontmatter_templates.md)\n99: \n100: ---\n101: \n102: ## 3. SKILL TEMPLATE (WITH BUNDLED RESOURCES)\n103: \n104: **Use for**: Skills with bundled resources (references, scripts, or assets)\n105: \n106: **Target**: 800-2000 lines (SKILL.md <1000 lines, rest in resources)\n107: \n108: **Size Constraints** (package_skill.py validation):\n109: - Max 5000 words (3000 recommended)\n110: - Max 3000 lines\n111: \n112: **Required Sections**: WHEN TO USE, SMART ROUTING, HOW IT WORKS, RULES (with ✅ ALWAYS, ❌ NEVER, ⚠️ ESCALATE IF), REFERENCES (or combined `SMART ROUTING & REFERENCES`)\n113: \n114: Packaging enforcement note:\n115: - `package_skill.py` fails if `REFERENCES` is missing and no approved combined `SMART ROUTING & REFERENCES` structure exists.\n116: \n117: **Recommended Sections**: SUCCESS CRITERIA, INTEGRATION POINTS, REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n118: \n119: ### Template\n120: \n121: ---\n122: name: example-skill\n123: description: Example skill demonstrating proper template structure with specific capabilities for semantic code search and context preservation workflows.\n124: allowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]\n125: version: 1.0.0\n126: ---\n127: \n128: <!-- Keywords: [KEYWORDS] -->\n129: \n130: # [Skill Title - Comprehensive Name]\n131: \n132: [One-sentence tagline followed by key capabilities overview]\n133: \n134: <!-- OPTIONAL: Include this block if skill has a supplemental navigation layer.\n135:      See skill_creation.md for authoring rules. -->\n136: <!-- Remove comment markers to activate:\n137: \n138: \\## 1. WHEN TO USE\n139: \n140: <!-- CRITICAL: This section contains ONLY activation triggers and use cases.\n141:      NO file references or navigation guides here - those go in Section 2. -->\n142: \n143: ### Activation Triggers\n144: \n145: **Use when**:\n146: - [Scenario 1 with context]\n147: - [Scenario 2 with context]\n148: - [Scenario 3 with context]\n149: \n150: **Keyword Triggers** (if applicable):\n151: - [Pattern 1 that triggers skill]\n152: - [Pattern 2 that triggers skill]\n153: \n154: ### Use Cases\n155: \n156: ### [Primary Use Case Category]\n157: \n158: [Content for primary use cases]\n159: \n160: ### [Secondary Use Case Category]\n161: \n162: [Content for secondary use cases]\n163: \n164: ### When NOT to Use\n165: \n166: **Do not use for**:\n167: - [Anti-pattern with rationale]\n168: - [Anti-pattern with rationale]\n169: - [Anti-pattern with rationale]\n170: \n171: ---\n172: \n173: \\## 2. SMART ROUTING\n174: \n175: <!-- CRITICAL: Keep one authoritative Smart Router Pseudocode block in this section.\n176:      Detection context may appear before pseudocode. Do NOT duplicate routing logic in separate lookup tables. -->\n177: \n178: ### [Primary Detection Signal]\n179: \n180: [Document the first routing signal clearly, for example project detection, stack detection, or mode detection.]\n181: \n182: ```bash\n183: # Example (replace with skill-specific detection)\n184: [ -f \"go.mod\" ] && STACK=\"GO\"\n185: [ -f \"package.json\" ] && STACK=\"NODEJS\"\n186: ```\n187: \n188: ### Phase Detection\n189: \n190: ```text\n191: TASK CONTEXT\n192:     |\n193:     +- STEP 0: Detect [project/stack/mode]\n194:     +- STEP 1: Score intents (top-2 when ambiguity is small)\n195:     +- Phase 1: Implementation\n196:     +- Phase 2: Testing/Debugging\n197:     +- Phase 3: Verification\n198: ```\n199: \n200: ### Resource Domains\n201: \n202: The router discovers markdown resources recursively from `references/` and `assets/` and then applies intent scoring from `INTENT_MODEL`.\n203: \n204: Knowledge is organized by domain mapping:\n205: \n206: ```text\n207: references/[domain]/...\n208: assets/[domain]/...\n209: ```\n210: \n211: - `references/[domain]/` for guidance, standards, and troubleshooting.\n212: - `assets/[domain]/` for templates, checklists, and reusable outputs.\n213: - `scripts/` for optional automation entrypoints when needed.\n214: \n215: ### Resource Loading Levels\n216: \n217: | Level       | When to Load             | Resources                    |\n218: | ----------- | ------------------------ | ---------------------------- |\n219: | ALWAYS      | Every skill invocation   | Baseline references          |\n220: | CONDITIONAL | If intent signals match  | Intent-mapped references     |\n221: | ON_DEMAND   | Only on explicit request | Deep-dive standards/templates|\n222: \n223: ### Smart Router Pseudocode\n224: \n225: #### Smart Router (Resilience Pattern)\n226: \n227: > Pattern: see [sk-doc smart-router resilience template](./skill_smart_router.md) for the full runtime discovery, guarded load, routing-key, and fallback reference.\n228: \n229: New skills fill in the domain-specific `INTENT_MODEL`, `RESOURCE_MAP`, loading levels, and routing key detector while keeping the resilience mechanics unchanged: discover resources at runtime, guard every path before loading, derive a routing key from the task or runtime, and return an `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK` checklist when confidence is too low.\n230: \n231: ```python\n232: from pathlib import Path\n233: \n234: SKILL_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent\n235: RESOURCE_BASES = (SKILL_ROOT / \"references\", SKILL_ROOT / \"assets\")\n236: DEFAULT_RESOURCE = \"references/[default].md\"\n237: \n238: INTENT_MODEL = {\n239:     \"PRIMARY\": {\"keywords\": [(\"[primary keyword]\", 4), (\"[phrase]\", 3)]},\n240:     \"DEBUGGING\": {\"keywords\": [(\"error\", 4), (\"failed\", 4), (\"debug\", 3)]},\n241:     \"VERIFICATION\": {\"keywords\": [(\"verify\", 4), (\"done\", 3), (\"complete\", 3)]},\n242: }\n243: \n244: RESOURCE_MAP = {\n245:     \"PRIMARY\": [\"references/[domain]/[primary].md\"],\n246:     \"DEBUGGING\": [\"assets/[domain]/checklists/debugging_checklist.md\"],\n247:     \"VERIFICATION\": [\"assets/[domain]/checklists/verification_checklist.md\"],\n248: }\n249: \n250: LOAD_LEVELS = {\n251:     \"PRIMARY\": \"STANDARD\",\n252:     \"DEBUGGING\": \"DEBUGGING\",\n253:     \"VERIFICATION\": \"MINIMAL\",\n254: }\n255: \n256: UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST = [\n257:     \"Confirm the routing key or runtime surface\",\n258:     \"Confirm the task intent\",\n259:     \"Provide one concrete input, error, or expected output\",\n260:     \"Confirm verification expectations before completion\",\n261: ]\n262: \n263: AMBIGUITY_DELTA = 1\n264: \n265: def _guard_in_skill(relative_path: str) -> str:\n266:     resolved = (SKILL_ROOT / relative_path).resolve()\n267:     resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT)\n268:     if resolved.suffix.lower() != \".md\":\n269:         raise ValueError(f\"Only markdown resources are routable: {relative_path}\")\n270:     return resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix()\n271: \n272: def discover_markdown_resources() -> set[str]:\n273:     docs = []\n274:     for base in RESOURCE_BASES:\n275:         if base.exists():\n276:             docs.extend(path for path in base.rglob(\"*.md\") if path.is_file())\n277:     return {doc.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix() for doc in docs}\n278: \n279: def get_routing_key(task, intents: list[str]) -> str:\n280:     override = str(getattr(task, \"routing_key\", \"\")).strip().lower()\n281:     if override:\n282:         return override\n283:     return (intents[0] if intents else \"unknown\").lower()\n284: \n285: def classify_intents(user_request, task=None):\n286:     text = (user_request or \"\").lower()\n287:     scores = {intent: 0 for intent in INTENT_MODEL}\n288:     for intent, cfg in INTENT_MODEL.items():\n289:         for keyword, weight in cfg[\"keywords\"]:\n290:             if keyword in text:\n291:                 scores[intent] += weight\n292: \n293:     ranked = sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda pair: pair[1], reverse=True)\n294:     primary, primary_score = ranked[0]\n295:     if primary_score == 0:\n296:         return (\"PRIMARY\", None, scores)\n297: \n298:     secondary, secondary_score = ranked[1]\n299:     if secondary_score > 0 and (primary_score - secondary_score) <= AMBIGUITY_DELTA:\n300:         return (primary, secondary, scores)\n301:     return (primary, None, scores)\n302: \n303: def route_[skill_name]_resources(user_request, task=None):\n304:     inventory = discover_markdown_resources()\n305:     primary, secondary, scores = classify_intents(user_request, task)\n306:     intents = [primary] + ([secondary] if secondary else [])\n307:     routing_key = get_routing_key(task, intents)\n308:     reference_prefix = f\"references/{routing_key}/\"\n309:     asset_prefix = f\"assets/{routing_key}/\"\n310:     keyed_refs = sorted(path for path in inventory if path.startswith(reference_prefix))\n311:     keyed_assets = sorted(path for path in inventory if path.startswith(asset_prefix))\n312:     loaded = []\n313:     seen = set()\n314: \n315:     def load_if_available(relative_path: str):\n316:         guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)\n317:         if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n318:             load(guarded)\n319:             loaded.append(guarded)\n320:             seen.add(guarded)\n321: \n322:     load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n323:     baseline_count = len(loaded)\n324:     if max(scores.values() or [0]) < 0.5:\n325:         return {\n326:             \"routing_key\": routing_key,\n327:             \"intents\": intents,\n328:             \"intent_scores\": scores,\n329:             \"load_level\": \"UNKNOWN_FALLBACK\",\n330:             \"needs_disambiguation\": True,\n331:             \"disambiguation_checklist\": UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST,\n332:             \"resources\": loaded,\n333:         }\n334: \n335:     for intent in intents:\n336:         for relative_path in RESOURCE_MAP.get(intent, []):\n337:             load_if_available(relative_path)\n338: \n339:     for relative_path in keyed_refs:\n340:         load_if_available(relative_path)\n341:     for relative_path in keyed_assets:\n342:         load_if_available(relative_path)\n343: \n344:     if routing_key == \"unknown\" or (len(loaded) == baseline_count and not keyed_refs):\n345:         return {\n346:             \"routing_key\": routing_key,\n347:             \"intents\": intents,\n348:             \"intent_scores\": scores,\n349:             \"notice\": f\"No keyed knowledge base found for routing key '{routing_key}'\",\n350:             \"resources\": loaded,\n351:         }\n352: \n353:     return {\"routing_key\": routing_key, \"intents\": intents, \"intent_scores\": scores, \"resources\": loaded}\n354: ```\n355: \n356: ---\n357: \n358: \\## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n359: \n360: ### [Primary Workflow] Overview\n361: \n362: [2-3 sentence explanation of the workflow]\n363: \n364: **Process Flow**:\n365: ```\n366: STEP 1: [Action Name]\n367:        ├─ [Sub-action with detail]\n368:        ├─ [Sub-action with detail]\n369:        └─ [Output description]\n370:        ↓\n371: STEP 2: [Action Name]\n372:        ├─ [Sub-action with detail]\n373:        └─ [Output description]\n374:        ↓\n375: STEP 3: [Action Name]\n376:        └─ [Final output]\n377: ```\n378: \n379: See [workflow-details.md](./references/workflow-details.md) for complete step-by-step guidance.\n380: \n381: ### [Key Component or Pattern]\n382: \n383: [Explanation of important architectural pattern or component]\n384: \n385: **Structure**:\n386: ```[language]\n387: # Show structure or pattern\n388: # With explanatory comments\n389: ```\n390: \n391: ### [Resource Usage Pattern]\n392: \n393: **How to use bundled resources**:\n394: \n395: **Scripts**: [When and how to invoke scripts]\n396: ```bash\n397: # Example script invocation\n398: [command-line-example]\n399: ```\n400: \n401: **References**: [When to load reference files]\n402: \n403: **Assets**: [When to use template/asset files]\n404: \n405: ### [Configuration or Setup]\n406: \n407: [Setup requirements, if any]\n408: \n409: ---\n410: \n411: <!-- NOTE: RULES section is REQUIRED by package_skill.py validation.\n412:      Subsections MUST be named ALWAYS, NEVER, and ESCALATE IF (or ESCALATE WHEN).\n413:      Use H3 by default; H4 is allowed when nested under phase headings.\n414:      Do NOT add horizontal dividers (---) between RULES subsections. -->\n415: \n416: \\## 4. RULES\n417: \n418: <!-- REQUIRED SUBSECTIONS (package_skill.py validation): -->\n419: <!-- - ALWAYS -->\n420: <!-- - NEVER -->\n421: <!-- - ESCALATE IF (or \"ESCALATE WHEN\") -->\n422: \n423: ### ALWAYS\n424: \n425: **ALWAYS do these without asking:**\n426: \n427: 1. **ALWAYS [critical rule with resource tie-in]**\n428:    - [Implementation detail]\n429:    - [Reference to bundled resource if applicable]\n430: \n431: 2. **ALWAYS [critical rule 2]**\n432:    - [Detail]\n433: \n434: 3. **ALWAYS [critical rule 3]**\n435:    - [Detail]\n436: \n437: 4. **ALWAYS [critical rule 4]**\n438:    - [Detail]\n439: \n440: 5. **ALWAYS [critical rule 5]**\n441:    - [Detail]\n442: \n443: ### NEVER\n444: \n445: **NEVER do these:**\n446: \n447: 1. **NEVER [anti-pattern]**\n448:    - [Why problematic]\n449:    - [Alternative approach]\n450: \n451: 2. **NEVER [anti-pattern]**\n452:    - [Why problematic]\n453: \n454: 3. **NEVER [anti-pattern]**\n455:    - [Why problematic]\n456: \n457: ### ESCALATE IF\n458: \n459: **Ask user when:**\n460: \n461: 1. **ESCALATE IF [ambiguous case]**\n462:    - [What's unclear]\n463:    - [What to ask]\n464: \n465: 2. **ESCALATE IF [blocking issue]**\n466:    - [What's blocked]\n467:    - [Resolution path]\n468: \n469: ---\n470: \n471: \\## 5. REFERENCES\n472: \n473: ### Core References\n474: \n475: - [reference-name.md](./references/reference-name.md) - Primary operational guidance\n476: - [workflow-name.md](./references/workflow-name.md) - End-to-end execution flow\n477: \n478: ### Templates and Assets\n479: \n480: - [template-name.md](./assets/template-name.md) - Reusable output template\n481: - [checklist-name.md](./assets/checklist-name.md) - Validation checklist\n482: \n483: ### Reference Loading Notes\n484: \n485: - Load only references needed for current intent.\n486: - Keep `SMART ROUTING` as the authority for loading rules.\n487: - Use combined heading `SMART ROUTING & REFERENCES` only if both concerns stay clear.\n488: \n489: ---\n490: \n491: \\## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n492: \n493: ### [Primary Workflow] Completion Checklist\n494: \n495: **[Workflow name] complete when**:\n496: - ✅ [Criterion 1]\n497: - ✅ [Criterion 2]\n498: - ✅ [Criterion 3]\n499: - ✅ [Criterion 4]\n500: - ✅ [Criterion 5]\n501: \n502: ### Quality Targets\n503: \n504: **Target metrics** (if applicable):\n505: - **[Metric 1]**: [Target value/threshold]\n506: - **[Metric 2]**: [Target value/threshold]\n507: - **[Metric 3]**: [Target value/threshold]\n508: \n509: ### Validation Success\n510: \n511: **Validation passes when**:\n512: - ✅ [Validation check 1]\n513: - ✅ [Validation check 2]\n514: - ✅ [Validation check 3]\n515: \n516: ---\n517: \n518: \\## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n519: \n520: ### [Integration System 1 - e.g., Validation Workflow]\n521: \n522: **[Validation Name]** (if applicable):\n523: - Triggers: [When it runs]\n524: - Purpose: [What it does]\n525: - Execution: [Performance characteristics]\n526: > **Note:** Run validation manually after file operations, or configure your environment for automatic execution.\n527: \n528: ### [Integration System 2 - e.g., Cross-Workflow Contract]\n529: \n530: **[Contract Name]**: [When it applies and what the skill must hand off]\n531: \n532: ### Tool Usage Guidelines\n533: \n534: **[Tool Name]**: [Specific usage pattern]\n535: \n536: **[Tool Name]**: [Specific usage pattern]\n537: \n538: **[Tool Name]**: [Specific usage pattern]\n539: \n540: ### Knowledge Base Dependencies\n541: \n542: **Required**:\n543: - `file-path` – Purpose, what happens if missing\n544: \n545: **Optional**:\n546: - `file-path` – Enhancement provided\n547: \n548: ### External Tools\n549: \n550: **[Tool Name]** (if needed):\n551: - Installation: [How to install]\n552: - Purpose: [Why needed]\n553: - Fallback: [What happens if unavailable]\n554: \n555: ---\n556: \n557: \\## 8. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n558: \n559: The router discovers reference, asset, and script docs dynamically. Start with `references/[primary].md`, `assets/[template].md`, and any skill-specific automation under `scripts/`, then load task-specific resources according to Section 2.\n560: \n561: Scripts: `scripts/[primary-helper]` when the skill ships automation; omit this line when no scripts exist.\n562: \n563: Related skills: `[related-skill]` for [relationship], `[other-skill]` for [relationship], and `system-spec-kit` when packet documentation or memory continuity applies.\n564: \n565: Install guide: [INSTALL_GUIDE.md](INSTALL_GUIDE.md) when the skill has installation or configuration steps.\n566: \n567: **Word Count Targets**:\n568: - Section 1 (WHEN TO USE): 150-200 lines\n569: - Section 2 (SMART ROUTING): 80-200 lines (routing logic + resource catalog)\n570: - Section 3 (HOW IT WORKS): 200-300 lines\n571: - Section 4 (RULES): 150-200 lines\n572: - Section 5 (REFERENCES): 40-120 lines\n573: - Section 6 (SUCCESS CRITERIA): 80-120 lines\n574: - Section 7 (INTEGRATION POINTS): 100-150 lines\n575: - Section 8 (REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES): 20-60 lines\n576: \n577: **Bundled Resources Structure (Monolithic)**:\n578: ```\n579: .opencode/skills/skill-name/       # Note: .opencode/skills/ (singular, NOT skills)\n580: ├── SKILL.md (800-1000 lines)\n581: └── Bundled Resources\n582:     ├── scripts/          - Executable automation\n583:     ├── references/       - Detailed documentation (flat or domain subfolders)\n584:     └── assets/           - Templates and examples (subfolders OK)\n585:         ├── opencode/     - OpenCode component templates (skills, agents, commands)\n586:         └── readme/        - README-shaped scaffolds (README, install guide)\n587: ```\n588: \n589: **Folder Organization Principle**:\n590: - **references/** = flat for small skills, domain subfolders for medium/complex skills\n591:   - Flat example: `references/global/core_standards.md`, `references/global/validation.md`\n592:   - Domain example: `references/backend/go/`, `references/frontend/react/`\n593: - **assets/** = Subfolders ALLOWED when organizing many files by category\n594:   - Group related templates together\n595:   - Example: `assets/skill/`, `assets/readme/`, `assets/flowcharts/`\n596: - **scripts/** = Typically flat, but subfolders OK for large script collections\n597: \n598: **Native Discovery**:\n599: - Skills auto-discovered from `.opencode/skills/*/SKILL.md` frontmatter\n600: - Skill name in frontmatter MUST match folder name\n601: - Skills appear as `skills_<name>` functions in OpenCode (hyphens → underscores)\n602: - Invoke via `Read(\".opencode/skills/<name>/SKILL.md\")`\n603: \n604: ---\n605: \n606: ## 4. SECTION-BY-SECTION CONTENT GUIDANCE\n607: \n608: ### Section 1: WHEN TO USE\n609: \n610: **Purpose**: Help the AI agent and users understand WHEN to activate this skill\n611: \n612: **Section Boundary Rule**: \"When to Use\" = WHEN (triggers only). File references belong in Section 2 (Smart Routing).\n613: \n614: **Essential Content** (ONLY these belong here):\n615: - Activation triggers (what conditions activate this skill)\n616: - Use case categories (2-4 categories)\n617: - Specific scenarios (3-5 per category)\n618: - Anti-patterns (\"When NOT to Use\")\n619: - Keyword triggers (optional)\n620: \n621: **Content that does NOT belong here** (move to Section 2 inline):\n622: - ❌ File references\n623: - ❌ Resource paths\n624: - ❌ Resource tables\n625: \n626: **Structure**:\n627: \n628: ### Activation Triggers\n629: \n630: **Use when**:\n631: - [Specific scenario with context]\n632: - [Specific scenario with context]\n633: \n634: **Keyword Triggers**:\n635: - [Pattern that activates skill]\n636: \n637: ### Use Cases\n638: \n639: ### [Use Case Category]\n640: \n641: [Content for use case]\n642: \n643: ### When NOT to Use\n644: \n645: **Skip this skill when:**\n646: - [Anti-pattern with rationale]\n647: \n648: **Writing Tips**:\n649: - Be specific: \"Generate JSDoc for functions\" not \"document code\"\n650: - Include context: Why each scenario benefits from this skill\n651: - Clear boundaries: Explicitly state what's out of scope\n652: - Trigger patterns: What keywords/patterns auto-activate skill\n653: - **NO file references** - those go in Section 2 (Smart Routing)\n654: \n655: **Word Budget**: 100-200 lines\n656: \n657: ---\n658: \n659: ### Section 2: SMART ROUTING (Required for All Skills)\n660: \n661: **Purpose**: Provide authoritative resource routing with scoped guards, recursive discovery, weighted scoring, and ambiguity handling.\n662: \n663: **Critical Rule**:\n664: ```\n665: ❌ WRONG: Section 2 with no explicit detection logic (project/stack/mode)\n666: ❌ WRONG: Separate use-case routing tables or navigation guides\n667: ✅ RIGHT: Detection context + merged resource domains/mapping + loading levels + one authoritative pseudocode block\n668: \n669: Section 2 typically contains five subsections:\n670: 1. Primary Detection Signal\n671: 2. Phase Detection\n672: 3. Resource Domains (including folder mapping)\n673: 4. Resource Loading Levels\n674: 5. Smart Router Pseudocode (authoritative)\n675: ```\n676: \n677: **Placement**: After Section 1 (WHEN TO USE), before Section 3 (HOW IT WORKS)\n678: \n679: **Essential Content**:\n680: - **Primary Detection Signal** - explicit stack/project/mode detection rule\n681: - **Phase Detection** - concise execution flow from detection to verification\n682: - **Resource Domains** - merged domain mapping + concise domain-level paths\n683: - **Resource Loading Levels** - ALWAYS/CONDITIONAL/ON_DEMAND table aligned to in-code behavior\n684: - **Smart Router Pseudocode** - scoped guard + recursive discovery + weighted scoring + top-2 ambiguity handling\n685: - **Router parity checklist** - include `_guard_in_skill()`, `discover_markdown_resources()`, `get_routing_key()`, `classify_intents()`, `load_if_available()`, and `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST`\n686: - **Unknown fallback behavior** - include `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST` for low-confidence intent routing where applicable\n687: \n688: **Structure**:\n689: \n690: \\## 2. SMART ROUTING\n691: \n692: ### [Primary Detection Signal]\n693: \n694: ```bash\n695: # Example detection logic\n696: [ -f \"go.mod\" ] && STACK=\"GO\"\n697: [ -f \"package.json\" ] && STACK=\"NODEJS\"\n698: ```\n699: \n700: ### Phase Detection\n701: \n702: ```text\n703: TASK CONTEXT\n704:     |\n705:     +- STEP 0: Detect project/stack/mode\n706:     +- STEP 1: Score intents (top-2 on ambiguity)\n707:     +- Phase 1: Implementation\n708:     +- Phase 2: Testing/Debugging\n709:     +- Phase 3: Verification\n710: ```\n711: \n712: ### Resource Domains\n713: \n714: The router discovers markdown resources recursively from `references/` and `assets/` and then applies intent scoring from `INTENT_MODEL`.\n715: \n716: ```text\n717: references/[domain]/...\n718: assets/[domain]/...\n719: ```\n720: \n721: - `references/[domain]/` for standards, architecture, and troubleshooting.\n722: - `assets/[domain]/` for checklists and templates.\n723: \n724: ### Resource Loading Levels\n725: \n726: | Level       | When to Load             | Resources                    |\n727: | ----------- | ------------------------ | ---------------------------- |\n728: | ALWAYS      | Every skill invocation   | Baseline references          |\n729: | CONDITIONAL | If intent signals match  | Intent-mapped references     |\n730: | ON_DEMAND   | Only on explicit request | Deep-dive standards/templates|\n731: \n732: ### Smart Router Pseudocode\n733: \n734: ```python\n735: # Authoritative router logic. See skill_smart_router.md for the full resilience pattern.\n736: # 1) Scope guard resource paths to current skill root\n737: # 2) Discover markdown resources recursively\n738: # 3) Derive a runtime routing key from task, stack, command, mode, or intent\n739: # 4) Score intents with weighted signals and keep top-2 when scores are close\n740: # 5) Load only guarded paths that exist, with UNKNOWN_FALLBACK on low confidence\n741: ```\n742: \n743: **Writing Tips**:\n744: - Start Section 2 with the strongest detection signal for this skill.\n745: - Keep resource domains and folder mapping in a single section.\n746: - Keep conditions measurable and tied to resource paths.\n747: - Keep `RESOURCE_MAP`, routing keys, and loading levels synchronized.\n748: - Keep one authoritative pseudocode block in Section 2.\n749: - Require scoped guards and recursive discovery in every router.\n750: - Use top-2 ambiguity handling when intent scores are close.\n751: - Avoid duplicate lookup tables, static file inventories, and unguarded `load()` calls.\n752: \n753: **Word Budget**: 80-200 lines\n754: \n755: ---\n756: \n757: ### Section 3: HOW IT WORKS\n758: \n759: **Purpose**: Explain the skill's workflow, architecture, and key patterns\n760: \n761: **Essential Content**:\n762: - Process flow (visual diagram using ASCII)\n763: - Key capabilities or components\n764: - Configuration or setup requirements\n765: - Examples of primary workflows\n766: - Flowchart supplements for complex logic (NEW - when logic blocks present)\n767: \n768: **Structure**:\n769: \n770: ### [Primary Workflow Name]\n771: \n772: [Brief explanation]\n773: \n774: **Process Flow**:\n775: \\`\\`\\`\n776: STEP 1: [Action]\n777:    ├─ [Sub-task]\n778:    └─ [Output]\n779:    ↓\n780: STEP 2: [Action]\n781:    └─ [Output]\n782: \\`\\`\\`\n783: \n784: **Example**:\n785: \\`\\`\\`[language]\n786: # Realistic example\n787: \\`\\`\\`\n788: \n789: **Writing Tips**:\n790: - Visual flows help comprehension (use ASCII diagrams)\n791: - Show, don't just tell (include code examples)\n792: - Progressive detail: Overview → specifics → edge cases\n793: - Link to references for deep dives\n794: - **Flowchart Supplements**: Add visual flowcharts before/after complex Python/YAML logic (see below)\n795: \n796: **Word Budget**: 150-300 lines\n797: \n798: ### Flowchart Supplements (For Complex Logic)\n799: \n800: **Purpose**: Add visual clarity to complex Python/YAML logic blocks without removing structured code\n801: \n802: **When to Use**:\n803: - Complex conditional logic (nested if/else, multiple branches)\n804: - Mode detection algorithms\n805: - Multi-step decision trees\n806: - Workflow routing logic\n807: - State machine transitions\n808: \n809: **Approach**:\n810: - **Supplement, don't replace**: Keep existing Python/YAML code intact\n811: - **Add flowcharts**: Place ASCII flowchart before or after code block\n812: - **Visual aid purpose**: Help quick understanding of logic flow\n813: \n814: **Structure**:\n815: \n816: ### [Logic Section Name]\n817: \n818: **[Brief explanation of what this logic does]**\n819: \n820: **Logic Flow**:\n821: \\`\\`\\`\n822: START\n823:   ↓\n824: [Check Condition A]\n825:   ↓\n826: A True? ─── NO ──→ [Path B]\n827:   │                    ↓\n828:   │              [Process B]\n829:   │                    ↓\n830:   YES              [Continue]\n831:   ↓\n832: [Process A]\n833:   ↓\n834: RESULT\n835: \\`\\`\\`\n836: \n837: **Implementation**:\n838: \\`\\`\\`python\n839: def example_logic(input):\n840:     \"\"\"Original Python logic preserved\"\"\"\n841:     if condition_a:\n842:         return process_a(input)\n843:     else:\n844:         return process_b(input)\n845: \\`\\`\\`\n846: \n847: **OR for configuration:**\n848: \n849: \\`\\`\\`yaml\n850: mode_detection:\n851:   trigger_patterns:\n852:     ticket: [\"$ticket\", \"create ticket\"]\n853:     story: [\"$story\", \"user story\"]\n854:   defaults:\n855:     mode: interactive\n856:     depth: 10\n857: \\`\\`\\`\n858: \n859: **Writing Tips**:\n860: - **Keep code**: Don't remove Python/YAML - it's precise and complete\n861: - **Add diagrams**: Flowcharts provide at-a-glance understanding\n862: - **Placement**:\n863:   - Flowchart FIRST if it aids comprehension before reading code\n864:   - Flowchart AFTER if it summarizes complex code\n865:   - Both before AND after for very complex logic\n866: - **Consistency**: Use same ASCII flowchart style as Smart Routing Diagram\n867: - **When to skip**: Simple 2-3 line logic doesn't need flowcharts\n868: \n869: **Example Use Cases**:\n870: - Mode detection with 5+ conditions → Flowchart + Python code\n871: - YAML configuration with complex triggers → Keep YAML, add decision tree diagram\n872: - Multi-step workflow routing → Flowchart showing paths, keep implementation code\n873: \n874: **Word Budget**: Variable (adds 10-30 lines per complex logic block)\n875: \n876: ---\n877: \n878: ### Section 4: RULES (REQUIRED)\n879: \n880: **Purpose**: Define mandatory behaviors, prohibited actions, and escalation triggers\n881: \n882: **Validation**: package_skill.py requires this section with specific subsections\n883: \n884: **Essential Content** (all three subsections REQUIRED):\n885: - ALWAYS rules (4-7 critical requirements)\n886: - NEVER rules (3-5 anti-patterns to avoid)\n887: - ESCALATE IF (3-5 situations requiring user input)\n888: \n889: **Structure**:\n890: \n891: ### ALWAYS\n892: \n893: **ALWAYS do these without asking:**\n894: \n895: 1. **ALWAYS [requirement]**\n896:    - [Why this matters]\n897:    - [Implementation detail]\n898: \n899: ### NEVER\n900: \n901: **NEVER do these:**\n902: \n903: 1. **NEVER [anti-pattern]**\n904:    - [Why problematic]\n905:    - [Alternative approach]\n906: \n907: ### ESCALATE IF\n908: \n909: **Ask user when:**\n910: \n911: 1. **ESCALATE IF [ambiguous situation]**\n912:    - [What's unclear]\n913:    - [What clarification needed]\n914: \n915: **Writing Tips**:\n916: - Use ALL CAPS for subsection headers: `ALWAYS`, `NEVER`, `ESCALATE IF` (or `ESCALATE WHEN`)\n917: - Be specific and actionable\n918: - Explain *why* for each rule (rationale matters)\n919: - Include implementation guidance\n920: - Present options to user for ESCALATE IF cases\n921: \n922: **Word Budget**: 100-200 lines\n923: \n924: ---\n925: \n926: ### Section 5: REFERENCES\n927: \n928: **Purpose**: Expose the operational references and templates the skill depends on.\n929: \n930: **Essential Content**:\n931: - Core references used during execution\n932: - Templates/assets used during output generation\n933: - Loading notes that stay consistent with Section 2 (SMART ROUTING)\n934: \n935: **Structure**:\n936: \n937: ### Core References\n938: - [reference-name.md](./references/reference-name.md) - Primary guidance\n939: \n940: ### Templates and Assets\n941: - [template-name.md](./assets/template-name.md) - Reusable output template\n942: \n943: ### Reference Loading Notes\n944: - Load only what current intent requires.\n945: - Keep Smart Routing as the single routing authority.\n946: \n947: **Word Budget**: 40-120 lines\n948: \n949: ---\n950: \n951: ### Section 6: SUCCESS CRITERIA\n952: \n953: **Purpose**: Define completion conditions and quality standards\n954: \n955: **Essential Content**:\n956: - Completion checklist (5-10 items)\n957: - Quality gates or thresholds\n958: - Validation requirements\n959: \n960: **Structure**:\n961: \n962: ### Task Completion Checklist\n963: \n964: **[Workflow name] Complete When:**\n965: \n966: - [ ] [Success criterion 1]\n967: - [ ] [Success criterion 2]\n968: - [ ] [Success criterion 3]\n969: \n970: ### Quality Gates\n971: \n972: **Before marking complete:**\n973: \n974: - **[Dimension]**: [Specific requirement]\n975: - **[Dimension]**: [Specific requirement]\n976: \n977: **Writing Tips**:\n978: - Use checkbox format `- [ ]` for checklists\n979: - Specific and measurable criteria\n980: - Include both completion and quality checks\n981: - Define thresholds numerically where possible\n982: \n983: **Word Budget**: 50-120 lines\n984: \n985: ---\n986: \n987: ### Section 7: INTEGRATION POINTS\n988: \n989: **Purpose**: Document how skill integrates with systems, tools, and workflow contracts\n990: \n991: **Essential Content**:\n992: - Validation workflow integration\n993: - Required workflow contracts and handoff rules\n994: - Tool usage patterns\n995: - Knowledge base dependencies\n996: - External tool requirements\n997: \n998: **Structure**:\n999: \n1000: ### Validation Workflow Integration\n1001: \n1002: **[Validation Name]**:\n1003: - Triggers: [When to run]\n1004: - Purpose: [What it validates]\n1005: \n1006: ### Cross-Workflow Contracts\n1007: \n1008: **[Contract Name]**: [When it applies and what the skill must hand off]\n1009: \n1010: ### Tool Usage Guidelines\n1011: \n1012: **[Tool]**: [Usage pattern]\n1013: \n1014: ### Knowledge Base Dependencies\n1015: \n1016: **Required**: [Files needed]\n1017: **Optional**: [Enhancing files]\n1018: \n1019: ### External Tools\n1020: \n1021: **[Tool Name]**:\n1022: - Installation: [How]\n1023: - Purpose: [Why]\n1024: \n1025: **Writing Tips**:\n1026: - Distinguish required vs. optional dependencies\n1027: - Provide installation/setup instructions for external tools\n1028: - Explain fallback behavior if optional resources missing\n1029: - Link related skills by name\n1030: \n1031: **Word Budget**: 50-150 lines\n1032: \n1033: ---\n1034: \n1035: ## 5. COMMON PITFALLS\n1036: \n1037: For the complete list of 8 common pitfalls with before/after examples, see:\n1038: → **[skill_creation.md § 5. COMMON PITFALLS](../../references/skill_creation.md#5-common-pitfalls)**\n1039: \n1040: **Quick Summary:**\n1041: 1. Generic descriptions → Be specific about capabilities\n1042: 2. Bloated SKILL.md → Move details to references/\n1043: 3. Missing bundled resources → Identify repeated code/docs\n1044: 4. Unclear triggers → Specific activation conditions\n1045: 5. Second-person language → Use imperative form\n1046: 6. Platform-specific claims → Stay platform-agnostic\n1047: 7. Multiline YAML descriptions → Keep single line\n1048: 8. Redundant routing tables → Keep routing authority in pseudocode\n1049: \n1050: ### Writing Style Quick Reference\n1051: \n1052: **DO**: Third-person voice (descriptions), imperative form (instructions), specific examples, rationale for rules\n1053: \n1054: **DON'T**: Second-person (\"You should...\"), vague descriptions, duplicate content, angle brackets in frontmatter\n1055: \n1056: ---\n1057: \n1058: ## 6. QUALITY CHECKLIST & QUICK REFERENCE\n1059: \n1060: ### Pre-Packaging Checklist\n1061: \n1062: **Before running package_skill.py:**\n1063: \n1064: Frontmatter:\n1065: □ YAML frontmatter present and valid\n1066: □ Required fields: name, description, allowed-tools\n1067: □ Name is hyphen-case (matches directory)\n1068: □ Description uses third-person voice\n1069: □ Description is specific (not generic)\n1070: □ No angle brackets in description\n1071: □ allowed-tools lists all tools used\n1072: \n1073: Structure:\n1074: □ H1 title with descriptive subtitle\n1075: □ Numbered H2 sections (1. WHEN TO USE, 2. SMART ROUTING, etc.)\n1076: □ H2 headings use ALL CAPS\n1077: □ Section separators (---) between major sections\n1078: □ No table of contents (forbidden in SKILL.md)\n1079: □ Proper heading hierarchy (H1 → H2 → H3)\n1080: □ SMART ROUTING section placed after WHEN TO USE, before HOW IT WORKS\n1081: \n1082: Content - Standard Sections:\n1083: □ WHEN TO USE section includes use cases + anti-patterns\n1084: □ HOW IT WORKS section explains workflow clearly\n1085: □ RULES section has ALWAYS, NEVER, ESCALATE IF\n1086: □ REFERENCES section lists core references/templates explicitly\n1087: □ SUCCESS CRITERIA section defines completion\n1088: □ INTEGRATION POINTS section documents dependencies\n1089: □ All bundled resources referenced from SKILL.md\n1090: □ No duplication between SKILL.md and references/\n1091: \n1092: Content - NEW Standardization (2025):\n1093: □ Section 1 (WHEN TO USE) contains ONLY activation triggers and use cases\n1094: □ Section 1 does NOT contain file-path routing logic\n1095: □ SMART ROUTING section exists (Section 2 - REQUIRED for all skills)\n1096: □ Section 2 includes explicit detection signal(s) (project/stack/mode as applicable)\n1097: □ Section 2 includes Phase Detection summary flow\n1098: □ Section 2 includes merged Resource Domains + folder mapping guidance\n1099: □ Section 2 includes scoped guard + recursive discovery markers\n1100: □ Section 2 includes weighted intent scoring + top-2 ambiguity handling\n1101: □ Section 2 includes Resource Loading Levels table\n1102: □ Section 2 includes one authoritative Smart Router Pseudocode block\n1103: □ Section 2 avoids duplicate routing lookup tables and static file inventories\n1104: □ Flowchart supplements added to complex logic blocks in Section 3 (where applicable)\n1105: □ Python/YAML code preserved (supplements, not replacements)\n1106: □ All ASCII diagrams use consistent style (when used)\n1107: \n1108: Quality:\n1109: □ SKILL.md under 5k words (<3k preferred)\n1110: □ Concrete examples included\n1111: □ Rationale provided for rules\n1112: □ Language is third-person (descriptions) or imperative (instructions)\n1113: □ Consistent heading format\n1114: □ All code blocks specify language\n1115: □ Links work correctly\n1116: □ Section 1 contains ONLY triggers/use cases (NO file references)\n1117: □ Section 2 Smart Router Pseudocode load() calls include file refs with descriptions\n1118: \n1119: ### Quick Reference Table\n1120: \n1121: | Element               | Requirement                | Example                                                                                            |\n1122: | --------------------- | -------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n1123: | **Filename**          | `SKILL.md` (exact case)    | ✅ `SKILL.md`  ❌ `skill.md`                                                                         |\n1124: | **Frontmatter**       | Required YAML with fields  | `name`, `description`, `allowed-tools`                                                             |\n1125: | **Name Format**       | `hyphen-case`              | ✅ `mcp-chrome-devtools`  ❌ `devtools_cli`                                                    |\n1126: | **Description Voice** | Third-person               | ✅ \"Use when...\"  ❌ \"You should...\"                                                                 |\n1127: | **H2 Format**         | Number + ALL CAPS          | ✅ `## 1. WHEN TO USE`                                                                            |\n1128: | **TOC**               | Forbidden in SKILL.md      | ❌ No table of contents                                                                             |\n1129: | **Sections**          | 5 required + 3 recommended | Required: WHEN TO USE, SMART ROUTING, HOW IT WORKS, RULES, REFERENCES (or combined `SMART ROUTING & REFERENCES`). Recommended: SUCCESS CRITERIA, INTEGRATION POINTS, REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES |\n1130: | **File Size**         | <5k words (<3k preferred)  | Move details to references/                                                                        |\n1131: | **Rules Format**      | ALWAYS, NEVER, ESCALATE IF | All caps headers, specific rules                                                                   |\n1132: | **Examples**          | Concrete and realistic     | Show actual use cases                                                                              |\n1133: \n1134: ### Template Selection Matrix\n1135: \n1136: | Characteristic        | Simple                    | Moderate                         | Complex                             |\n1137: | --------------------- | ------------------------- | -------------------------------- | ----------------------------------- |\n1138: | **Workflows**         | Single                    | Single                           | Multiple modes                      |\n1139: | **Bundled Resources** | None                      | Some (refs/scripts/assets)       | Extensive                           |\n1140: | **Total Lines**       | 400-800                   | 800-2000                         | 2000-5000                           |\n1141: | **SKILL.md Lines**    | 400-800                   | 800-1000                         | <3000                               |\n1142: | **Sections**          | 5 required core           | 5 required + recommended sections | 5 required per mode + overview       |\n1143: | **Example Skills**    | mcp-chrome-devtools | system-spec-kit, sk-code | sk-doc, sk-git |\n1144: \n1145: ### Validation Command Reference\n1146: \n1147: ```bash\n1148: # Validate skill structure (REQUIRED before claiming complete)\n1149: python .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/package_skill.py .opencode/skills/[skill-name] --check\n1150: \n1151: # Validation checks:\n1152: # - Frontmatter: name (hyphen-case), description (no <>), allowed-tools (array format), version\n1153: # - Required sections: WHEN TO USE, SMART ROUTING, HOW IT WORKS, RULES, REFERENCES\n1154: # - RULES subsections: ✅ ALWAYS, ❌ NEVER, ⚠️ ESCALATE IF\n1155: # - Size constraints: max 5000 words, max 3000 lines\n1156: \n1157: # Native discovery:\n1158: # - Skills auto-discovered from .opencode/skills/*/SKILL.md frontmatter\n1159: # - Skills appear as skills_* functions in OpenCode\n1160: # - Invoke via Read(\".opencode/skills/<name>/SKILL.md\")\n1161: ```\n1162: \n1163: ---\n1164: \n1165: ## 7. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n1166: \n1167: ### Templates\n1168: - [frontmatter_templates.md](../frontmatter_templates.md) - Frontmatter by document type\n1169: - [skill_asset_template.md](./skill_asset_template.md) - Asset file creation guide\n1170: - [skill_reference_template.md](./skill_reference_template.md) - Reference file templates\n1171: \n1172: ### Standards\n1173: - [core_standards.md](../../references/global/core_standards.md) - Document type rules\n1174: - [skill_creation.md](../../references/skill_creation.md) - Complete skill creation workflow\n\n(End of file - total 1174 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: SKILL.md File Templates - Creation Guide\ndescription: Templates and guidelines for creating effective SKILL.md files for AI agent skills with complete scaffolds and section guidance.\n---\n\n# SKILL.md File Templates - Creation Guide\n\nTemplates for creating SKILL.md files with proper structure, frontmatter, and required sections.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose of SKILL.md Files\n\nSKILL.md files define AI agent skills - reusable capabilities that extend an agent's functionality for specific domains or workflows. A well-crafted SKILL.md:\n\n- **Triggers automatically** when relevant patterns are detected\n- **Guides the agent** through specialized workflows\n- **Maintains consistency** across conversations","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_md_template.md","time":{"start":1780204870141,"end":1780204870158}},"id":"prt_e7c7a97bd001mlkZMQnTFu64TI","sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","messageID":"msg_e7c7a8dac001fYFQWMEsKOY24Q"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780204870633,"sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_d2nwfgn6x5o0_2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_asset_template.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_asset_template.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Skill Asset File Templates\n3: description: Templates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Skill Asset File Templates - Creation Guidelines\n7: \n8: Templates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\n9: \n10: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n11: \n12: ### Location & Naming\n13: \n14: **Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/assets/`\n15: \n16: **Naming Convention:** snake_case with appropriate extension\n17: \n18: | ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |\n19: |---------------|-----------------|\n20: | `frontmatter_templates.md` | `FrontmatterTemplates.md` (PascalCase) |\n21: | `config_examples.yaml` | `config-examples.yaml` (kebab-case) |\n22: | `validation_checklist.md` | `ValidationChecklist.MD` (wrong case) |\n23: | `emoji_reference.md` | `emojiReference.md` (camelCase) |\n24: \n25: ### When to Create Assets\n26: \n27: **Create an asset file when:**\n28: - Templates users apply repeatedly\n29: - Reference data >50 lines and self-contained\n30: - Multiple examples of same pattern exist\n31: - Lookup tables or decision matrices needed\n32: - Template variations for different scenarios\n33: \n34: **Keep in SKILL.md when:**\n35: - Content <30 lines\n36: - Tightly coupled to workflow logic\n37: - Needs to be visible immediately (not progressive disclosure)\n38: - Part of core instructions (RULES, WORKFLOW sections)\n39: \n40: ---\n41: \n42: ## 2. ASSET FILE TYPES\n43: \n44: ### Template Files\n45: **Purpose**: Provide copy-paste starting points for common tasks\n46: \n47: **Naming**: `[content-type]_templates.md`\n48: - Example: `frontmatter_templates.md`, `structure_templates.md`\n49: \n50: **Structure**:\n51: - One template per section\n52: - Include field descriptions\n53: - Show complete examples\n54: - Explain when to use each template\n55: \n56: **Use cases**:\n57: - Document templates (SKILL.md, commands, knowledge files)\n58: - Configuration templates (YAML, JSON)\n59: - Code templates (functions, classes, modules)\n60: \n61: ### Reference Files\n62: **Purpose**: Provide lookup tables, decision trees, or reference data\n63: \n64: **Naming**: `[topic]_reference.md`\n65: - Example: `emoji_reference.md`, `validation_reference.md`\n66: \n67: **Structure**:\n68: - Tables or lists for quick lookup\n69: - Decision matrices\n70: - Classification systems\n71: - Standards and conventions\n72: \n73: **Use cases**:\n74: - Emoji selection guides\n75: - File type classifications\n76: - Validation rule sets\n77: - Naming conventions\n78: \n79: ### Example Files\n80: **Purpose**: Show working examples of skill outputs\n81: \n82: **Naming**: `[topic]_examples.md`\n83: - Example: `optimization_examples.md`, `skill_examples.md`\n84: \n85: **Structure**:\n86: - Before/after comparisons\n87: - Annotated examples\n88: - Multiple variations\n89: - Anti-patterns to avoid\n90: \n91: **Use cases**:\n92: - Complete skill applications\n93: - Common patterns\n94: - Edge cases\n95: - Quality standards\n96: \n97: ### Guide Files\n98: **Purpose**: Detailed how-to guides for complex processes\n99: \n100: **Naming**: `[process]_guide.md`\n101: - Example: `packaging_guide.md`, `distribution_guide.md`\n102: \n103: **Structure**:\n104: - Step-by-step instructions\n105: - Troubleshooting sections\n106: - Best practices\n107: - Common pitfalls\n108: \n109: **Use cases**:\n110: - Multi-step processes\n111: - Advanced techniques\n112: - Workflow deep-dives\n113: - Integration guides\n114: \n115: ---\n116: \n117: ## 3. DOCUMENT STRUCTURE\n118: \n119: ### Title and Intro\n120: \n121: **CRITICAL: The intro after the H1 title must be 1-2 SHORT sentences only.**\n122: \n123: ```markdown\n124: ---\n125: title: [Title]\n126: description: [One-line description - same as intro]\n127: ---\n128: \n129: # [Title]\n130: \n131: [1-2 SHORT sentences only. Brief hook/summary. NO subsections, NO headers here.]\n132: \n133: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n134: \n135: ### Purpose\n136: \n137: [Why this asset exists]\n138: \n139: ### Usage\n140: \n141: [How to use this asset - copy instructions, customization notes]\n142: \n143: ---\n144: \n145: \\## 2. [Content Section]\n146: \n147: [The actual template/checklist/snippet content]\n148: \n149: ---\n150: \n151: ## N. Related Resources (optional, if present must be last)\n152: \n153: [Links to related files]\n154: \n155: ```\n156: \n157: > **WARNING: DO NOT duplicate content between intro and OVERVIEW section.**\n158: > The intro is a hook; OVERVIEW provides the details.\n159: \n160: #### GOOD Intro Structure\n161: \n162: ```markdown\n163: # Git Commit Templates\n164: \n165: Copy-paste templates for creating well-structured commit messages.\n166: \n167: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n168: \n169: ### Purpose\n170: \n171: Provides consistent commit message formats for atomic commits...\n172: \n173: ### Usage\n174: \n175: Copy the appropriate template based on commit type...\n176: \n177: ---\n178: \n179: \\## 2. COMMIT TEMPLATES\n180: ...\n181: ```\n182: \n183: #### BAD Intro Structure (too long, has subsections)\n184: \n185: ```markdown\n186: # Git Commit Templates\n187: \n188: Copy-paste templates for creating well-structured commit messages.\n189: \n190: ### Core Principle    ← WRONG: No headers in intro!\n191: Atomic commits with clear intent = maintainable history.\n192: \n193: ### When to Use       ← WRONG: This belongs in OVERVIEW section!\n194: - Creating new features\n195: - Fixing bugs\n196: \n197: ---\n198: ```\n199: \n200: ### Intro vs OVERVIEW Content Placement\n201: \n202: | Content Type          | Intro (after H1) | OVERVIEW Section       |\n203: | --------------------- | ---------------- | ---------------------- |\n204: | 1-2 sentence summary  | ✅ YES            | ❌ NO (don't repeat)    |\n205: | Core Principle        | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (in Purpose)     |\n206: | When to Use           | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (in Purpose)     |\n207: | How to copy/customize | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (in Usage)       |\n208: | Prerequisites         | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (in Usage)       |\n209: | Any H2/H3 subsections | ❌ NEVER          | ✅ YES                  |\n210: \n211: ---\n212: \n213: ## 4. STANDARD ASSET STRUCTURE\n214: \n215: **Template**:\n216: \n217: ```markdown\n218: # Asset Title - Descriptive Subtitle\n219: \n220: Brief introduction (1-2 sentences) explaining what this asset provides and when to use it.\n221: \n222: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n223: \n224: ### Purpose\n225: \n226: [Why this asset exists, what problem it solves]\n227: \n228: ### Usage\n229: \n230: [How to use this asset - copy instructions, customization notes]\n231: \n232: ---\n233: \n234: \\## 2. SECTION NAME\n235: \n236: **Key Points**:\n237: - Point 1\n238: - Point 2\n239: - Point 3\n240: \n241: **Template**:\n242: ```[language]\n243: # Template content here\n244: # With explanatory comments\n245: ```\n246: \n247: **Field Guidelines**:\n248: \n249: **`field_name`**:\n250: - Description of field\n251: - Format requirements\n252: - Example: `value-example`\n253: \n254: **Complete Example**:\n255: ```[language]\n256: # Complete working example\n257: # Ready to copy and adapt\n258: ```\n259: \n260: ---\n261: \n262: \\## 3. SECTION NAME\n263: \n264: [Continue pattern...]\n265: \n266: ---\n267: \n268: ## N. RELATED RESOURCES\n269: \n270: [Links to related files - MUST be last section if present]\n271: \n272: ```\n273: \n274: ---\n275: \n276: ## 5. LOGIC REPRESENTATION PATTERNS\n277: \n278: **Purpose**: Guidelines for representing logic, workflows, and decision trees in asset files using structured formats instead of prose.\n279: \n280: **Why Structured Logic?**\n281: - **Clarity**: Executable-style logic is easier to understand than prose\n282: - **AI-Friendly**: LLMs parse structured logic better than narrative descriptions\n283: - **Maintainability**: Changes to logic are more visible in structured formats\n284: - **Consistency**: Same patterns across all asset files\n285: \n286: ### When to Use Each Format\n287: \n288: **Use Python Pseudo-Code When:**\n289: - Complex branching logic (multiple IF/ELIF/ELSE conditions)\n290: - Function/method definitions with clear inputs/outputs\n291: - State management or algorithmic processes\n292: - Validation or transformation logic\n293: - Examples: Mode detection, validation pipelines, decision functions\n294: \n295: **Use YAML Structures When:**\n296: - Configuration data (settings, options, parameters)\n297: - Pipeline definitions (multi-step workflows with clear phases)\n298: - Hierarchical workflows (nested processes)\n299: - Metadata structures (categorization, tagging)\n300: - Examples: Workflow definitions, configuration templates, feature matrices\n301: \n302: **Use Markdown Decision Trees When:**\n303: - Simple branching logic (2-5 branches)\n304: - Visual flow representation (user-facing paths)\n305: - Classification systems (type determination)\n306: - Quick decision guides\n307: - Examples: Document type selection, frontmatter requirements\n308: \n309: **Keep Markdown Prose When:**\n310: - Explanatory text and conceptual overviews\n311: - Narrative examples with context\n312: - Best practices guidance\n313: - Introductions and summaries\n314: \n315: ---\n316: \n317: ## 6. DECISION LOGIC EXAMPLES\n318: \n319: **Purpose**: Demonstrate how to convert markdown prose into structured decision logic.\n320: \n321: ### Python Pseudo-Code: Mode Detection\n322: \n323: **Before (Markdown Prose)**:\n324: ```markdown\n325: Check user input for mode indicators:\n326: - If \"$quick\" is present, use quick mode with auto-scaling depth\n327: - If \"$ticket\" is present, use ticket mode with depth 10\n328: - Otherwise, use interactive mode with depth 10\n329: ```\n330: \n331: **After (Python Pseudo-Code)**:\n332: ```python\n333: def detect_mode(request):\n334:     \"\"\"Detect execution mode from user request markers\"\"\"\n335: \n336:     if '$quick' in request:\n337:         mode = 'quick'\n338:         depth = 'auto_scale_1_to_5'\n339:     elif '$ticket' in request:\n340:         mode = 'ticket'\n341:         depth = 'depth_10_rounds'\n342:     else:\n343:         # DEFAULT TO INTERACTIVE\n344:         mode = 'interactive'\n345:         depth = 'depth_10_rounds'\n346: \n347:     return mode, depth\n348: ```\n349: \n350: ### Markdown Decision Tree: Frontmatter Requirements\n351: \n352: **Before (Markdown Prose)**:\n353: ```markdown\n354: Different document types have different frontmatter requirements:\n355: - SKILL.md files must have frontmatter with name, description, and allowed-tools\n356: - Command files must have frontmatter with description and argument-hint\n357: - Knowledge files should not have frontmatter\n358: - Spec files typically don't have frontmatter\n359: ```\n360: \n361: **After (Markdown Decision Tree)**:\n362: ```\n363: Document type?\n364: ├─> SKILL.md       → MUST have frontmatter (name, description, allowed-tools)\n365: ├─> Command        → MUST have frontmatter (description, argument-hint, allowed-tools)\n366: ├─> Knowledge      → MUST NOT have frontmatter (remove if present)\n367: ├─> Spec           → SHOULD NOT have frontmatter (suggest removal)\n368: └─> README         → No specific requirement (usually none)\n369: ```\n370: \n371: ### Python Pseudo-Code: Validation Logic\n372: \n373: **Before (Markdown Prose)**:\n374: ```markdown\n375: Validate the document structure:\n376: 1. Check if required sections exist\n377: 2. Verify section ordering is correct\n378: 3. Ensure frontmatter is valid (if present)\n379: ```\n380: \n381: **After (Python Pseudo-Code)**:\n382: ```python\n383: def validate_document(doc, doc_type):\n384:     \"\"\"Validate document structure and content\"\"\"\n385: \n386:     errors = []\n387: \n388:     # Check required sections\n389:     required_sections = get_required_sections(doc_type)\n390:     for section in required_sections:\n391:         if section not in doc.sections:\n392:             errors.append(f\"Missing required section: {section}\")\n393: \n394:     # Verify section ordering\n395:     expected_order = get_section_order(doc_type)\n396:     actual_order = [s.name for s in doc.sections]\n397:     if actual_order != expected_order:\n398:         errors.append(f\"Section order incorrect. Expected: {expected_order}\")\n399: \n400:     # Validate frontmatter\n401:     if doc.has_frontmatter:\n402:         frontmatter_errors = validate_frontmatter(doc.frontmatter, doc_type)\n403:         errors.extend(frontmatter_errors)\n404: \n405:     return errors\n406: ```\n407: \n408: ---\n409: \n410: ## 7. WORKFLOW PATTERNS\n411: \n412: **Purpose**: Show how to represent multi-step workflows using YAML structures.\n413: \n414: ### YAML Pipeline: Document Creation Workflow\n415: \n416: **Before (Markdown List)**:\n417: ```markdown\n418: 1. Analyze the request and determine document type\n419: 2. Select appropriate template\n420: 3. Populate template with content\n421: 4. Validate structure and content\n422: 5. Apply formatting standards\n423: 6. Run quality checks\n424: ```\n425: \n426: **After (YAML Pipeline)**:\n427: ```yaml\n428: document_creation_workflow:\n429:   phase_1_analysis:\n430:     action: \"Analyze request and determine document type\"\n431:     output: \"Document type classification\"\n432:     validation: \"Type must be one of: SKILL, Command, Knowledge, Spec, README\"\n433: \n434:   phase_2_template_selection:\n435:     action: \"Select appropriate template based on document type\"\n436:     output: \"Template file path\"\n437:     depends_on: \"phase_1_analysis\"\n438: \n439:   phase_3_population:\n440:     action: \"Populate template with user-provided content\"\n441:     output: \"Draft document with filled sections\"\n442:     depends_on: \"phase_2_template_selection\"\n443: \n444:   phase_4_validation:\n445:     action: \"Validate structure, frontmatter, section ordering\"\n446:     output: \"Validation report (errors/warnings)\"\n447:     depends_on: \"phase_3_population\"\n448: \n449:   phase_5_formatting:\n450:     action: \"Apply code standards (spacing, headers)\"\n451:     output: \"Formatted document\"\n452:     depends_on: \"phase_4_validation\"\n453: \n454:   phase_6_quality_check:\n455:     action: \"Review checklist + run AI quality evaluation\"\n456:     output: \"Quality notes and improvement recommendations\"\n457:     depends_on: \"phase_5_formatting\"\n458: ```\n459: \n460: ### YAML Configuration: Feature Flags\n461: \n462: **Before (Markdown Table)**:\n463: ```markdown\n464: | Feature           | Default | Description                         |\n465: | ----------------- | ------- | ----------------------------------- |\n466: | strict_validation | true    | Enforce all validation rules        |\n467: | auto_fix          | false   | Automatically fix formatting issues |\n468: | frontmatter_check | true    | Validate frontmatter per document type |\n469: ```\n470: \n471: **After (YAML Configuration)**:\n472: ```yaml\n473: feature_flags:\n474:   strict_validation:\n475:     default: true\n476:     description: \"Enforce all validation rules without warnings\"\n477:     values: [true, false]\n478: \n479:   auto_fix:\n480:     default: false\n481:     description: \"Automatically fix formatting issues during validation\"\n482:     values: [true, false]\n483:     warning: \"Use with caution - may change document semantics\"\n484: \n485:   frontmatter_check:\n486:     default: true\n487:     description: \"Validate frontmatter fields per document type\"\n488:     values: [true, false]\n489:     enforcement_level: \"error\"\n490: ```\n491: \n492: ### YAML Workflow: Multi-Branch Decision Process\n493: \n494: **Before (Markdown Prose)**:\n495: ```markdown\n496: The system should detect when to generate variants:\n497: - If user explicitly requests options (shows me options, variations, different approaches)\n498: - If complexity is high (7+) and uncertainty signals are present (not sure, what would work)\n499: - Otherwise, generate single solution\n500: \n501: Variant count depends on complexity:\n502: - Simple: 2-3 variants\n503: - Standard: 3-5 variants\n504: - Complex: 5-10 variants\n505: ```\n506: \n507: **After (YAML Multi-Branch)**:\n508: ```yaml\n509: variant_generation_logic:\n510:   triggers:\n511:     explicit:\n512:       keywords: [\"show me options\", \"variations\", \"different approaches\", \"multiple designs\"]\n513:       action: \"Generate variants immediately\"\n514:       priority: \"high\"\n515: \n516:     implicit:\n517:       conditions:\n518:         - \"complexity >= 7\"\n519:         - \"uncertainty_signals present\"\n520:       uncertainty_signals: [\"not sure\", \"what would work\", \"best approach\"]\n521:       action: \"Generate variants with uncertainty disclaimer\"\n522:       priority: \"medium\"\n523: \n524:     default:\n525:       action: \"Generate single optimal solution\"\n526:       priority: \"low\"\n527: \n528:   variant_count_guidelines:\n529:     simple:\n530:       complexity_range: [1, 3]\n531:       variant_count: \"2-3\"\n532: \n533:     standard:\n534:       complexity_range: [4, 6]\n535:       variant_count: \"3-5\"\n536: \n537:     complex:\n538:       complexity_range: [7, 10]\n539:       variant_count: \"5-10\"\n540: \n541:     user_specified:\n542:       action: \"Honor user's requested count\"\n543:       override: true\n544: ```\n545: \n546: ---\n547: \n548: ## 8. CONFIGURATION TEMPLATES\n549: \n550: **Purpose**: Demonstrate structured data formats for configuration and metadata.\n551: \n552: ### YAML: Tool Configuration\n553: \n554: ```yaml\n555: tool_configuration:\n556:   name: \"document-validator\"\n557:   version: \"2.1.0\"\n558: \n559:   settings:\n560:     validation:\n561:       strictness: \"high\"  # low | medium | high\n562:       fail_on_warnings: false\n563:       ignore_patterns:\n564:         - \"*.draft.md\"\n565:         - \"temp/**\"\n566: \n567:     formatting:\n568:       max_line_length: 100\n569:       heading_style: \"atx\"    # atx | setext\n570: \n571:     output:\n572:       format: \"json\"          # json | yaml | markdown\n573:       verbosity: \"normal\"     # minimal | normal | verbose\n574:       show_suggestions: true\n575: \n576:   rules:\n577:     frontmatter:\n578:       required_for: [\"SKILL.md\", \"commands\"]\n579:       forbidden_for: [\"knowledge\"]\n580:       optional_for: [\"README.md\"]\n581: \n582:     sections:\n583:       numbering: \"sequential\"  # sequential | hierarchical | none\n584: ```\n585: \n586: ### Python: Data Structures\n587: \n588: ```python\n589: # Classification matrix for document types\n590: DOCUMENT_CLASSIFICATIONS = {\n591:     \"SKILL.md\": {\n592:         \"category\": \"skill\",\n593:         \"requires_frontmatter\": True,\n594:         \"required_fields\": [\"name\", \"description\", \"allowed-tools\"],\n595:         \"optional_fields\": [\"tags\", \"category\", \"version\"],\n596:         \"max_lines\": 900,\n597:         \"required_sections\": [\"OBJECTIVE\", \"RULES\", \"WORKFLOW\", \"SUCCESS CRITERIA\"],\n598:     },\n599: \n600:     \"command\": {\n601:         \"category\": \"command\",\n602:         \"requires_frontmatter\": True,\n603:         \"required_fields\": [\"description\", \"argument-hint\"],\n604:         \"optional_fields\": [\"allowed-tools\", \"example\"],\n605:         \"max_lines\": 300,\n606:         \"required_sections\": [],\n607:     },\n608: \n609:     \"knowledge\": {\n610:         \"category\": \"knowledge\",\n611:         \"requires_frontmatter\": False,\n612:         \"required_fields\": [],\n613:         \"optional_fields\": [],\n614:         \"max_lines\": 500,\n615:         \"required_sections\": [],\n616:     },\n617: }\n618: \n619: # Validation severity levels\n620: VALIDATION_LEVELS = {\n621:     \"MUST\": {\n622:         \"severity\": \"error\",\n623:         \"blocking\": True,\n624:         \"examples\": [\"Required sections missing\", \"Invalid frontmatter syntax\"],\n625:     },\n626: \n627:     \"SHOULD\": {\n628:         \"severity\": \"warning\",\n629:         \"blocking\": False,\n630:         \"examples\": [\"Line length exceeds 100\", \"Inconsistent list bullet style\"],\n631:     },\n632: \n633:     \"MAY\": {\n634:         \"severity\": \"info\",\n635:         \"blocking\": False,\n636:         \"examples\": [\"Consider adding examples\", \"Section could be split\"],\n637:     },\n638: }\n639: ```\n640: \n641: ---\n642: \n643: ## 9. TEMPLATE GUIDELINES\n644: \n645: ### Naming Conventions\n646: \n647: **File Names** (snake_case required):\n648: - Format: `[topic]_[type].md`\n649: - Use underscores, not hyphens (snake_case)\n650: - Lowercase only\n651: - Descriptive and specific\n652: - Examples:\n653:   - ✅ `frontmatter_templates.md`\n654:   - ✅ `validation_reference.md`\n655:   - ✅ `config_examples.yaml`\n656:   - ✅ `packaging_guide.md`\n657:   - ❌ `templates.md` (too generic)\n658:   - ❌ `FrontmatterTemplates.md` (wrong case)\n659:   - ❌ `frontmatter-templates.md` (hyphens not allowed)\n660: \n661: **Type-Specific Patterns**:\n662: \n663: | Asset Type | Naming Pattern           | snake_case Examples          |\n664: | ---------- | ------------------------ | ---------------------------- |\n665: | Template   | `[content]_templates.md` | `frontmatter_templates.md`   |\n666: | Reference  | `[topic]_reference.md`   | `emoji_reference.md`         |\n667: | Example    | `[topic]_examples.md`    | `optimization_examples.md`   |\n668: | Guide      | `[process]_guide.md`     | `packaging_guide.md`         |\n669: | Checklist  | `[topic]_checklist.md`   | `validation_checklist.md`    |\n670: \n671: **Section Names**:\n672: - Use title case\n673: - Be descriptive but concise\n674: - Number if sequential: `1. Template Name`\n675: \n676: ### Content Organization\n677: \n678: **Progressive Disclosure**:\n679: 1. **Introduction**: What this is, why it exists (1-2 sentences)\n680: 2. **Sections**: Each covers one topic completely\n681: 3. **Examples**: Show, don't just tell\n682: 4. **Quick Reference**: Summary at end (optional)\n683: \n684: **Section Structure**:\n685: - **Purpose**: Why this section exists\n686: - **Guidelines**: How to use the content\n687: - **Template**: Copy-paste starting point\n688: - **Example**: Complete working example\n689: \n690: ### Formatting Standards\n691: \n692: **Code Blocks**:\n693: - Always specify language: ` ```yaml `, ` ```markdown `, ` ```bash `\n694: - Include comments explaining non-obvious parts\n695: - Show complete, runnable examples\n696: - Use placeholder values that are obviously placeholders\n697: \n698: **Placeholders**:\n699: - Format: `[descriptive-name]` or `your-value-here`\n700: - Examples:\n701:   - ✅ `[skill-name]`, `[feature-description]`, `your-project-name`\n702:   - ❌ `xxx`, `placeholder`, `FIXME`\n703: \n704: **Lists**:\n705: - Use `-` for unordered lists\n706: - Use `1.` for ordered lists\n707: - Nested lists indent by 2 spaces\n708: - Keep items parallel in structure\n709: \n710: **Tables**:\n711: - Include header row\n712: - Align consistently (usually left-aligned)\n713: - Keep rows concise (1-2 lines)\n714: - Use for comparisons or reference data\n715: \n716: ### Writing Style\n717: \n718: **Clarity**:\n719: - Write for someone unfamiliar with your skill\n720: - Define domain-specific terms on first use\n721: - Use active voice: \"Create the file\" not \"The file should be created\"\n722: - Be concise but complete\n723: \n724: **Examples**:\n725: - Every template should have a complete example\n726: - Show real-world usage, not toy examples\n727: - Include common variations\n728: - Annotate non-obvious parts\n729: \n730: **Consistency**:\n731: - Use same terminology throughout\n732: - Follow patterns from other assets in the skill\n733: - Match style of SKILL.md\n734: - Use consistent formatting\n735: \n736: ---\n737: \n738: ## 10. ASSET FILE CHECKLIST\n739: \n740: **Before creating an asset file, verify**:\n741: \n742: ```markdown\n743: Structure:\n744: □ Title with descriptive subtitle\n745: □ Introduction paragraph (1-2 sentences)\n746: □ Numbered sections\n747: □ Horizontal rules (---) between major sections\n748: \n749: Content:\n750: □ Each template has complete example\n751: □ Field descriptions explain purpose and format\n752: □ Placeholders are obviously placeholders\n753: □ Examples are realistic and working\n754: □ No references to undefined sections\n755: \n756: Quality:\n757: □ File name follows conventions ([topic]_[type].md)\n758: □ All code blocks specify language\n759: □ No spelling or grammar errors\n760: □ Links work correctly\n761: \n762: Integration:\n763: □ SKILL.md references this asset where appropriate\n764: □ Asset complements (doesn't duplicate) SKILL.md content\n765: □ File size appropriate (typically 100-800 lines)\n766: □ Content is self-contained (doesn't require external context)\n767: ```\n768: \n769: ---\n770: \n771: ## 11. EXAMPLES FROM THIS SKILL\n772: \n773: ### Example 1: Template File\n774: \n775: **File**: `frontmatter_templates.md`\n776: **Purpose**: Provide YAML frontmatter templates for different document types\n777: **Structure**:\n778: - Introduction explaining frontmatter purpose\n779: - One section per document type (SKILL.md, commands, knowledge files)\n780: - Each section includes: required fields, template, field guidelines, complete example\n781: \n782: **Key Features**:\n783: - Clear separation by document type\n784: - Field-by-field explanations\n785: - Complete working examples\n786: - Guidance on when to use vs. not use\n787: \n788: ### Example 2: Structure File\n789: \n790: **File**: `structure_templates.md`\n791: **Purpose**: Show correct document structure for each file type\n792: **Structure**:\n793: - TOC listing all templates\n794: - One section per document type\n795: - Section order requirements\n796: - Quick validation checklist\n797: \n798: **Key Features**:\n799: - Visual structure examples\n800: - Enforcement level specified\n801: - Complete document templates\n802: - Section ordering rules\n803: \n804: ### Example 3: Reference File\n805: \n806: **File**: `llmstxt_templates.md`\n807: **Purpose**: Templates for creating llms.txt files (AI-friendly site maps)\n808: **Structure**:\n809: - Format explanation\n810: - Template sections for different scenarios\n811: - Field descriptions\n812: - Complete examples\n813: - Best practices\n814: \n815: **Key Features**:\n816: - Multiple template variations\n817: - Integration instructions\n818: - Troubleshooting guidance\n819: - Real-world examples\n820: \n821: ---\n822: \n823: ## 12. ASSET MAINTENANCE\n824: \n825: ### When to Update Assets\n826: \n827: **Update asset files when**:\n828: - New template variations emerge\n829: - User feedback reveals confusion\n830: - Standards or conventions change\n831: - New use cases discovered\n832: - Examples become outdated\n833: \n834: **Version control**:\n835: - Note significant changes in skill version bump\n836: - Keep examples current with latest patterns\n837: - Remove deprecated templates\n838: - Add migration notes for breaking changes\n839: \n840: ### Deprecation Strategy\n841: \n842: **If removing a template**:\n843: 1. Mark as deprecated in section header: `## DEPRECATED: Template Name`\n844: 2. Explain why deprecated and what to use instead\n845: 3. Keep for 1-2 skill versions (with deprecation warning)\n846: 4. Remove after migration period\n847: \n848: **Example**:\n849: ```markdown\n850: ## DEPRECATED: OLD TEMPLATE NAME\n851: \n852: ⚠️ **This template is deprecated as of v3.0.0**\n853: \n854: **Use instead**: `new_template_name.md` (see Section 2)\n855: \n856: **Migration**: Replace X with Y in your existing files\n857: ```\n858: \n859: ---\n860: \n861: ## 13. BEST PRACTICES SUMMARY\n862: \n863: **DO**:\n864: - ✅ Create assets for reference data >50 lines\n865: - ✅ Include complete, working examples\n866: - ✅ Use clear, descriptive file names\n867: - ✅ Reference from SKILL.md where relevant\n868: - ✅ Keep assets focused (one topic per file)\n869: - ✅ Use consistent formatting\n870: \n871: **DON'T**:\n872: - ❌ Duplicate SKILL.md core content in assets\n873: - ❌ Create assets for tiny snippets (<30 lines)\n874: - ❌ Use generic file names (`templates.md`)\n875: - ❌ Mix multiple topics in one asset file\n876: - ❌ Create assets that require external context\n877: - ❌ Forget to update SKILL.md references\n878: - ❌ Include incomplete or broken examples\n879: \n880: ---\n881: \n882: ## 14. ASSET FILE NAMING QUICK REFERENCE\n883: \n884: **Location**: `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/assets/`\n885: \n886: **Format**: snake_case (underscores, lowercase)\n887: \n888: | Asset Type | Naming Pattern           | Example                    | Purpose                    |\n889: | ---------- | ------------------------ | -------------------------- | -------------------------- |\n890: | Templates  | `[content]_templates.md` | `frontmatter_templates.md` | Copy-paste starting points |\n891: | References | `[topic]_reference.md`   | `emoji_reference.md`       | Lookup tables, decisions   |\n892: | Examples   | `[topic]_examples.md`    | `optimization_examples.md` | Working code examples      |\n893: | Guides     | `[process]_guide.md`     | `packaging_guide.md`       | Step-by-step how-tos       |\n894: | Checklists | `[topic]_checklist.md`   | `validation_checklist.md`  | Verification lists         |\n895: \n896: **Naming Rules**:\n897: - ✅ Use snake_case: `frontmatter_templates.md`\n898: - ✅ Lowercase only: `config_examples.yaml`\n899: - ❌ No hyphens: `frontmatter-templates.md`\n900: - ❌ No PascalCase: `FrontmatterTemplates.md`\n901: \n902: ---\n903: \n904: ## 15. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n905: \n906: ### Templates\n907: - [frontmatter_templates.md](../frontmatter_templates.md) - Frontmatter by document type\n908: - [skill_md_template.md](./skill_md_template.md) - If converting to skill\n909: - [skill_reference_template.md](./skill_reference_template.md) - Reference file templates\n910: - [llmstxt_templates.md](../llmstxt_templates.md) - llms.txt file templates\n911: \n912: ### Standards\n913: - [core_standards.md](../../references/global/core_standards.md) - Document type rules\n914: - [skill_creation.md](../../references/skill_creation.md) - Full skill creation workflow\n\n(End of file - total 914 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Skill Asset File Templates\ndescription: Templates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\n---\n\n# Skill Asset File Templates - Creation Guidelines\n\nTemplates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Location & Naming\n\n**Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/assets/`\n\n**Naming Convention:** snake_case with appropriate extension\n\n| ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |\n|---------------|-----------------|\n| `frontmatter_templates.md` | `FrontmatterTemplates.md` (PascalCase) |","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_asset_template.md","time":{"start":1780204870619,"end":1780204870632}},"id":"prt_e7c7a9a010015RiD1hSgdWGT0A","sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","messageID":"msg_e7c7a8dac001fYFQWMEsKOY24Q"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780204870820,"sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_d2nwfgn6x5o0_3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/template_rules.json"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/template_rules.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"version\": \"1.2.0\",\n3:   \"description\": \"Machine-readable template specifications for automated documentation validation - aligned with all 9 templates\",\n4:   \"documentTypes\": {\n5:     \"readme\": {\n6:       \"description\": \"README.md files for projects, components, and features\",\n7:       \"requiredSections\": [\n8:         \"overview\"\n9:       ],\n10:       \"recommendedSections\": [\n11:         \"quick_start\",\n12:         \"troubleshooting\",\n13:         \"related\"\n14:       ],\n15:       \"optionalSections\": [\n16:         \"structure\",\n17:         \"features\",\n18:         \"configuration\",\n19:         \"usage_examples\",\n20:         \"faq\"\n21:       ],\n22:       \"sectionEmojis\": {\n23:         \"overview\": \"\\ud83d\\udcd6\",\n24:         \"quick_start\": \"\\ud83d\\ude80\",\n25:         \"structure\": \"\\ud83d\\udcc1\",\n26:         \"features\": \"\\u26a1\",\n27:         \"configuration\": \"\\u2699\\ufe0f\",\n28:         \"usage_examples\": \"\\ud83d\\udca1\",\n29:         \"usage\": \"\\ud83d\\udca1\",\n30:         \"troubleshooting\": \"\\ud83d\\udee0\\ufe0f\",\n31:         \"faq\": \"\\u2753\",\n32:         \"related_documents\": \"\\ud83d\\udcda\",\n33:         \"related_resources\": \"\\ud83d\\udd17\",\n34:         \"related\": \"\\ud83d\\udcda\",\n35:         \"patterns\": \"\\ud83d\\udca1\",\n36:         \"maintenance\": \"\\ud83d\\udd04\",\n37:         \"best_practices\": \"\\ud83c\\udf93\",\n38:         \"complete_template\": \"\\ud83d\\udccb\",\n39:         \"checklist\": \"\\u2705\"\n40:       },\n41:       \"sectionAliases\": {\n42:         \"related documents\": \"related\",\n43:         \"related resources\": \"related\",\n44:         \"related_documents\": \"related\",\n45:         \"related_resources\": \"related\",\n46:         \"usage examples\": \"usage_examples\",\n47:         \"quick start\": \"quick_start\",\n48:         \"best practices\": \"best_practices\",\n49:         \"best practices summary\": \"best_practices\",\n50:         \"complete template\": \"complete_template\",\n51:         \"readme checklist\": \"checklist\",\n52:         \"readme maintenance\": \"maintenance\"\n53:       },\n54:       \"tocRequired\": false,\n55:       \"tocAnchorFormat\": \"double_dash\",\n56:       \"tocUppercaseRequired\": true,\n57:       \"h2EmojiRequired\": false,\n58:       \"h2UppercaseRequired\": true,\n59:       \"firstSectionName\": \"overview\",\n60:       \"lastSectionPattern\": \"related\"\n61:     },\n62:     \"skill\": {\n63:       \"description\": \"SKILL.md files for OpenCode skills\",\n64:       \"requiredSections\": [\n65:         \"when_to_use\",\n66:         \"smart_routing\",\n67:         \"how_it_works\",\n68:         \"rules\"\n69:       ],\n70:       \"recommendedSections\": [\n71:         \"success_criteria\",\n72:         \"integration_points\",\n73:         \"related_resources\"\n74:       ],\n75:       \"optionalSections\": [\n76:         \"external_resources\"\n77:       ],\n78:       \"sectionEmojis\": {\n79:         \"when_to_use\": \"\\ud83c\\udfaf\",\n80:         \"smart_routing\": \"\\ud83e\\udded\",\n81:         \"how_it_works\": \"\\ud83d\\udee0\\ufe0f\",\n82:         \"rules\": \"\\ud83d\\udccb\",\n83:         \"success_criteria\": \"\\ud83c\\udfc6\",\n84:         \"integration_points\": \"\\ud83d\\udd0c\",\n85:         \"external_resources\": \"\\ud83d\\udcda\",\n86:         \"related_resources\": \"\\ud83d\\udd17\",\n87:   