{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780204907028,"sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","part":{"id":"prt_e7c7b2a13001HLY0m71KlaIPvb","messageID":"msg_e7c7b211d0016iIzc4TTGX6KPL","sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","snapshot":"e4992af896c5e7cb137cb9dde5c354491caa9e61","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780204908139,"sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_n2agm463qdvs_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/frontmatter_templates.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/frontmatter_templates.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: YAML Frontmatter Templates\n3: description: Templates and validation rules for YAML frontmatter across all document types in the OpenCode ecosystem.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # YAML Frontmatter Templates - Document Type Reference\n7: \n8: Templates and validation rules for YAML frontmatter by document type.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n13: \n14: ### What Is YAML Frontmatter?\n15: \n16: **YAML frontmatter** is a metadata block at the beginning of markdown files, delimited by `---` markers. It provides machine-readable configuration that controls how AI agents and tools process the document.\n17: \n18: ```yaml\n19: ---\n20: name: skill-name\n21: description: What this skill does\n22: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Bash\n23: ---\n24: \n25: # Document Content Starts Here\n26: ```\n27: \n28: **Core Purpose**:\n29: - **Tool configuration** - Define which AI tools a skill/command can use\n30: - **Discovery** - Enable programmatic listing and searching of skills/commands\n31: - **Argument parsing** - Specify expected inputs for commands\n32: - **Metadata storage** - Version, category, tags for organization\n33: \n34: **Key Difference from Inline Metadata**:\n35: - YAML frontmatter = Machine-parseable, strict format, at file start\n36: - Inline metadata = Human-readable, flexible format, anywhere in document\n37: \n38: ### Document Types and Frontmatter Requirements\n39: \n40: | Document Type | Frontmatter Required? | Reason |\n41: |---------------|----------------------|--------|\n42: | **SKILL.md** | ✅ **Required** | AI needs metadata to discover and invoke skills |\n43: | **Command** | ✅ **Required** | Arguments and tools must be declared |\n44: | **Knowledge** | ❌ **Forbidden** | Pure content, no programmatic interface |\n45: | **Spec** | ❌ **Not recommended** | Use inline metadata for flexibility |\n46: | **README** | ⚪ **Optional** | Usually none, unless documenting a skill |\n47: \n48: ### Core Characteristics\n49: \n50: | Characteristic | Description |\n51: |----------------|-------------|\n52: | **Delimiter syntax** | Must start and end with `---` on separate lines |\n53: | **Position** | Must be at the very beginning of the file (line 1) |\n54: | **YAML format** | Key-value pairs, no nested objects for required fields |\n55: | **Single-line values** | Description must be on one line (parser limitation) |\n56: | **Case-sensitive** | Field names are lowercase (`name`, not `Name`) |\n57: \n58: ### How Frontmatter Is Parsed\n59: \n60: ```\n61: File loaded by OpenCode\n62:          │\n63:          ├─► Check line 1 for opening `---`\n64:          │   └─► Not found? → No frontmatter (may be error for SKILL/Command)\n65:          │\n66:          ├─► Find closing `---` (within first 20 lines)\n67:          │   └─► Not found? → Malformed frontmatter error\n68:          │\n69:          ├─► Parse YAML between delimiters\n70:          │   └─► Invalid YAML? → Parse error\n71:          │\n72:          └─► Validate required fields by document type\n73:              └─► Missing required? → Validation error\n74: ```\n75: \n76: ### Progressive Validation\n77: \n78: ```\n79: Level 1: Structural Check\n80:          └─ Delimiters present and properly formatted\n81:             ↓\n82: Level 2: Field Presence\n83:          └─ Required fields exist for document type\n84:             ↓\n85: Level 3: Field Format\n86:          └─ Values match expected patterns (e.g., lowercase-with-hyphens)\n87: ```\n88: \n89: ---\n90: \n91: ## 2. WHEN TO ADD FRONTMATTER\n92: \n93: ### Add Frontmatter When\n94: \n95: **Programmatic Interface Needed**:\n96: - Document is a SKILL.md that AI agents invoke\n97: - Document is a command triggered via `/command-name`\n98: - Document needs tool restrictions (`allowed-tools`)\n99: - Document requires argument specification\n100: \n101: **Discovery Required**:\n102: - Skills/commands need to appear in listings\n103: - Metadata enables search and filtering\n104: - Version tracking needed\n105: \n106: **By Document Type**:\n107: \n108: | Document Type | Add Frontmatter? | Required Fields | Optional Fields |\n109: |---------------|------------------|-----------------|-----------------|\n110: | **SKILL.md** | ✅ Always | `name`, `description`, `allowed-tools` | `tags`, `category`, `version` |\n111: | **Command** | ✅ Always | `description`, `argument-hint`, `allowed-tools` | `name`, `model`, `version` |\n112: | **Knowledge** | ❌ Never | — | — |\n113: | **Spec** | ❌ Avoid | — | Use inline metadata instead |\n114: | **README** | ⚪ Rarely | Only if in `.opencode/skills/*/` | — |\n115: \n116: ### Remove Frontmatter When\n117: \n118: **Content-Only Documents**:\n119: - Knowledge files (reference documentation)\n120: - Spec files (planning documents)\n121: - General markdown files\n122: \n123: **Why Remove from Knowledge/Spec**:\n124: - Frontmatter implies programmatic interface\n125: - These documents are pure content\n126: - Adds confusion about document purpose\n127: \n128: ### Decision Framework\n129: \n130: ```\n131: Is this document invoked programmatically?\n132: ├─► YES\n133: │   │\n134: │   ├─► Is it a SKILL.md?\n135: │   │   └─► Add frontmatter: name, description, allowed-tools\n136: │   │\n137: │   └─► Is it a Command?\n138: │       └─► Add frontmatter: description, argument-hint, allowed-tools\n139: │\n140: └─► NO\n141:     │\n142:     ├─► Is it a Knowledge file?\n143:     │   └─► Remove frontmatter if present\n144:     │\n145:     ├─► Is it a Spec file?\n146:     │   └─► Remove frontmatter, use inline metadata\n147:     │\n148:     └─► Is it a README?\n149:         ├─► In .opencode/skills/*/? → Optional skill-style frontmatter\n150:         └─► Elsewhere? → No frontmatter needed\n151: ```\n152: \n153: ### Frontmatter Field Summary\n154: \n155: | Field | SKILL.md | Command | Purpose |\n156: |-------|----------|---------|---------|\n157: | `name` | ✅ Required | ⚪ Optional | Identifier (lowercase-with-hyphens) |\n158: | `description` | ✅ Required | ✅ Required | One-line explanation of purpose |\n159: | `allowed-tools` | ✅ Required | ✅ Required | Comma-separated tool list |\n160: | `argument-hint` | ❌ N/A | ✅ Required | Syntax hint: `<required> [optional]` |\n161: | `model` | ❌ N/A | ⚪ Optional | Override default model (rarely used) |\n162: | `version` | ⚪ Optional | ⚪ Optional | Semantic version |\n163: | `tags` | ⚪ Optional | ❌ N/A | Categorization keywords |\n164: \n165: ---\n166: \n167: ## 3. FIELD REFERENCE\n168: \n169: ### `name` Field\n170: \n171: **Purpose**: Unique identifier for skills\n172: \n173: **Format Requirements**:\n174: - Pattern: `^[a-z][a-z0-9-]*$`\n175: - Style: `lowercase-with-hyphens`\n176: - Should match directory name\n177: \n178: **Examples**:\n179: ```yaml\n180: # GOOD\n181: name: document-style-validator\n182: name: git-commit\n183: name: system-spec-kit\n184: \n185: # BAD\n186: name: DocumentStyleValidator  # No uppercase\n187: name: document_style_validator  # No underscores\n188: name: 123-skill  # Cannot start with number\n189: ```\n190: \n191: ### `description` Field\n192: \n193: **Purpose**: Human-readable explanation of what the skill/command does. Also feeds the Skill Advisor's lexical-lane scoring — the description's keyword density is what makes the skill discoverable to the model.\n194: \n195: **Format Requirements**:\n196: - One to two sentences maximum\n197: - **MUST be on a single line** (parser limitation)\n198: - See **Description Budget & Trim Style** below for length targets and content rules\n199: \n200: **Critical Warning**:\n201: \n202: > ⚠️ **YAML Multiline Strings Are Not Parsed**\n203: >\n204: > The skill parser does not handle YAML multiline block format. Keep your description on a single line after the colon.\n205: >\n206: > ```yaml\n207: > # ❌ BAD - Will not be parsed correctly\n208: > description:\n209: >   This is my skill description\n210: >   spanning multiple lines.\n211: >\n212: > # ✅ GOOD - Single line after colon\n213: > description: This is my skill description all on one line.\n214: > ```\n215: >\n216: > **Note**: Prettier and other formatters may auto-format long descriptions to multiline. If this happens, manually revert to single-line format.\n217: \n218: **Examples**:\n219: ```yaml\n220: # GOOD\n221: description: Validates markdown document structure against style guide requirements\n222: description: Four-phase debugging framework for browser console errors and CSS issues\n223: \n224: # BAD\n225: description: Validates  # Too short\n226: description:  # Empty\n227: ```\n228: \n229: ### Description Budget & Trim Style\n230: \n231: The Claude Code harness imposes two limits that authors don't see directly:\n232: \n233: | Constant | Value | Source |\n234: |----------|------:|--------|\n235: | Per-skill soft target | **≤ 130 chars** | Project convention; routing-keyword density stays high |\n236: | Per-command soft target | **≤ 110 chars** | Project convention; commands are terser by nature |\n237: | Per-item hard cap | **1,536 chars** | Claude Code internal limit (combined `description` + `when_to_use`) |\n238: | Project soft-ceiling | **5,600 chars** | Total of all project descriptions; leaves ~2,400-char headroom for Claude Code built-ins under the default `SLASH_COMMAND_TOOL_CHAR_BUDGET = 8000` |\n239: \n240: When project total exceeds the 8,000-char default, Claude Code **silently drops** the longest descriptions from its available-skills list. Skills stay invocable explicitly, but the model can no longer auto-suggest them. (Packet 083 had to trim 36 descriptions because the project had grown to ~10,050 chars and 15 skills were dropped.)\n241: \n242: **Trim style — DROP**:\n243: - Product enumerations (`ClickUp/Notion/Figma/Chrome…`)\n244: - Stack lists (`Webflow/HTML/CSS/JS/Motion.dev/GSAP…`) — see *Stack-agnostic phrasing* below\n245: - Marketing prose (`Mandatory for…`, `Provides…efficient…`, `…best-in-class…`)\n246: - Parenthetical jargon (`(gold battery, staleness model, exclude-rule confidence tiers)`)\n247: \n248: **Trim style — KEEP**:\n249: - Skill name token (the literal skill name appearing in the description boosts the explicit-author lane)\n250: - Primary verb (`orchestrate`, `validate`, `dispatch`, `audit`)\n251: - Primary domain noun (`MCP`, `code-review`, `prompts`, `git workflow`)\n252: - Mode suffixes (`:auto`, `:confirm`, `:apply`) — these are advisor trigger tokens\n253: - Numeric specifics (`9 steps`, `5-dim scoring`, `4 MCP servers`) — they signal real capability\n254: \n255: **Stack-agnostic phrasing** (project rule): never enumerate specific stacks (Webflow / Go / Next.js / Python frameworks…) in skill descriptions. The smart router detects the active stack at dispatch time; baking stacks into the description ages poorly and consumes routing-keyword budget that should go to the verb + domain noun.\n256: \n257: **Before/after example** (sk-code, packet 083, 545 → 125 chars):\n258: \n259: ```yaml\n260: # Before — 545 chars: enumerated stacks + library lists + marketing prose\n261: description: \"Multi-stack coding standards, references, and assets. Provides surface-aware code-quality patterns, checklists, and verification recipes for Webflow frontend (vanilla HTML/CSS/JS animation: Motion.dev, GSAP, Lenis, HLS, Swiper, FilePond, CDN deployment), cross-stack Motion.dev animation guidance, and OpenCode system code (JavaScript, TypeScript, Python, Shell, JSON/JSONC, MCP server code, agents, commands, skills). Smart-routing internals auto-detect the active stack and load matching standards; unsupported stacks ask for disambiguation.\"\n262: \n263: # After — 125 chars: skill name implicit, verb+domain noun preserved, smart-router phrase kept\n264: description: \"Multi-stack coding standards and verification. Smart router auto-detects the active surface and loads matching code patterns.\"\n265: ```\n266: \n267: The trimmed version retains every routing-keyword the advisor cares about (`coding`, `standards`, `verification`, `surface`, `code patterns`) while losing the brittle stack enumeration that would have to be edited every time a library is added.\n268: \n269: **Validation at create-time**: `quick_validate.py` warns when descriptions exceed the soft target and hard-fails at 1,536 chars. Run `/doctor skill-budget :auto` periodically to detect accumulated drift across the project.\n270: \n271: ### `allowed-tools` Field\n272: \n273: **Purpose**: Restricts which AI tools the skill/command can use\n274: \n275: **Format Requirements**:\n276: - Comma-separated list\n277: - Order by frequency of use (most common first)\n278: - Use exact tool names\n279: \n280: **Common Tools**:\n281: | Tool | Purpose |\n282: |------|---------|\n283: | `Read` | Read file contents |\n284: | `Write` | Create/overwrite files |\n285: | `Edit` | Modify existing files |\n286: | `Bash` | Execute shell commands |\n287: | `Grep` | Search file contents |\n288: | `Glob` | Find files by pattern |\n289: | `WebFetch` | Fetch web content |\n290: | `Task` | Spawn sub-agents |\n291: \n292: **Examples**:\n293: ```yaml\n294: # Common patterns\n295: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash\n296: allowed-tools: Read, Grep, Glob\n297: allowed-tools: Read, Bash, WebFetch\n298: \n299: # MCP tools\n300: allowed-tools: Read, mcp__semantic-search__semantic_search\n301: ```\n302: \n303: ### `argument-hint` Field (Commands Only)\n304: \n305: **Purpose**: Shows expected command syntax in `/help` output\n306: \n307: **Format Conventions**:\n308: | Syntax | Meaning | Example |\n309: |--------|---------|---------|\n310: | `<arg>` | Required argument | `<query>` |\n311: | `[arg]` | Optional argument | `[--verbose]` |\n312: | `[:mode]` | Mode suffix | `[:auto\\|:confirm]` |\n313: \n314: **Examples**:\n315: ```yaml\n316: argument-hint: <query>\n317: argument-hint: <task> [:auto|:confirm]\n318: argument-hint: <name> [type] [--force]\n319: argument-hint: [--confirm]\n320: ```\n321: \n322: ### `model` Field (Commands Only)\n323: \n324: **Purpose**: Override default AI model for command execution\n325: \n326: **Usage**: Use sparingly - only for commands requiring complex reasoning\n327: \n328: ```yaml\n329: # Only use for genuinely complex workflows\n330: model: opus\n331: ```\n332: \n333: ---\n334: \n335: ## 4. DOCUMENT TYPE TEMPLATES\n336: \n337: ### SKILL.md Frontmatter Template\n338: \n339: **Required Fields**: `name`, `description`, `allowed-tools`\n340: \n341: ```yaml\n342: ---\n343: name: skill-name\n344: description: Brief one-line description of what this skill does and when to use it\n345: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep\n346: ---\n347: ```\n348: \n349: **Complete Example**:\n350: ```yaml\n351: ---\n352: name: code-systematic-debugging\n353: description: Four-phase debugging framework for browser console errors, CSS layout issues, JavaScript animations, and platform-specific frontend bugs\n354: allowed-tools: Read, Bash, Grep\n355: ---\n356: ```\n357: \n358: ### Command Frontmatter Template\n359: \n360: **Required Fields**: `description`, `argument-hint`, `allowed-tools`\n361: \n362: ```yaml\n363: ---\n364: description: Brief description of what this command does\n365: argument-hint: <required_arg> [optional_arg]\n366: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Bash\n367: ---\n368: ```\n369: \n370: **Complete Example**:\n371: ```yaml\n372: ---\n373: description: Generate properly structured command files with correct YAML frontmatter\n374: argument-hint: <name> [purpose]\n375: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Bash\n376: ---\n377: ```\n378: \n379: ### Knowledge File (No Frontmatter)\n380: \n381: **Rule**: Knowledge files should **NOT** have YAML frontmatter.\n382: \n383: ```markdown\n384: # ❌ BEFORE (incorrect)\n385: ---\n386: name: document-style-guide\n387: description: Style guide for documentation\n388: ---\n389: \n390: # Document Style Guide\n391: \n392: Content...\n393: \n394: # ✅ AFTER (correct)\n395: # Document Style Guide\n396: \n397: Content...\n398: ```\n399: \n400: ### Spec File (Inline Metadata Instead)\n401: \n402: **Rule**: Specs use inline metadata, not YAML frontmatter.\n403: \n404: ```markdown\n405: # Feature Name - Spec\n406: \n407: **Date**: 2025-01-15\n408: **Version**: 1.0\n409: **Priority**: HIGH\n410: \n411: Brief introduction...\n412: ```\n413: \n414: **Rationale**: Specs evolve rapidly during planning. YAML frontmatter adds formality that slows iteration.\n415: \n416: ---\n417: \n418: ## 5. VALIDATION RULES\n419: \n420: ### Validation by Document Type\n421: \n422: ```yaml\n423: validation_rules:\n424:   SKILL:\n425:     frontmatter_required: true\n426:     required_fields:\n427:       - name\n428:       - description\n429:       - allowed-tools\n430:     optional_fields:\n431:       - tags\n432:       - category\n433:       - version\n434:     field_formats:\n435:       name:\n436:         pattern: \"^[a-z][a-z0-9-]*$\"\n437:         description: \"lowercase-with-hyphens\"\n438:       description:\n439:         min_length: 10\n440:         max_length: 200\n441:       allowed-tools:\n442:         type: \"comma-separated-list\"\n443: \n444:   Command:\n445:     frontmatter_required: true\n446:     required_fields:\n447:       - description\n448:       - argument-hint\n449:       - allowed-tools\n450:     optional_fields:\n451:       - name\n452:       - model\n453:       - version\n454:     field_formats:\n455:       description:\n456:         min_length: 10\n457:         max_length: 100\n458:       argument-hint:\n459:         pattern: \"contains < or [\"\n460: \n461:   Knowledge:\n462:     frontmatter_required: false\n463:     action_if_present: \"remove\"\n464: \n465:   Spec:\n466:     frontmatter_required: false\n467:     action_if_present: \"suggest_removal\"\n468: \n469:   README:\n470:     frontmatter_required: false\n471:     action_if_present: \"no_action\"\n472: ```\n473: \n474: ### Validation Checklist\n475: \n476: **Structural Checks**:\n477: - [ ] File starts with `---` on line 1\n478: - [ ] Closing `---` found within first 20 lines\n479: - [ ] Valid YAML syntax between delimiters\n480: \n481: **Field Presence (SKILL.md)**:\n482: - [ ] `name` field present\n483: - [ ] `description` field present\n484: - [ ] `allowed-tools` field present\n485: \n486: **Field Presence (Command)**:\n487: - [ ] `description` field present\n488: - [ ] `argument-hint` field present\n489: - [ ] `allowed-tools` field present\n490: \n491: **Field Format**:\n492: - [ ] `name` is lowercase-with-hyphens\n493: - [ ] `description` is single line, 10-200 chars\n494: - [ ] `allowed-tools` is comma-separated list\n495: - [ ] `argument-hint` uses `<required>` and `[optional]` syntax\n496: \n497: ---\n498: \n499: ## 6. COMMON FIXES\n500: \n501: ### Missing Frontmatter\n502: \n503: **SKILL.md without frontmatter**:\n504: ```yaml\n505: # ADD at beginning of file:\n506: ---\n507: name: inferred-from-directory\n508: description: Inferred from H1 subtitle or first paragraph\n509: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Bash\n510: ---\n511: ```\n512: \n513: ### Missing Fields\n514: \n515: ```yaml\n516: # BEFORE (missing allowed-tools)\n517: ---\n518: name: my-skill\n519: description: My skill description\n520: ---\n521: \n522: # AFTER (field added)\n523: ---\n524: name: my-skill\n525: description: My skill description\n526: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Bash\n527: ---\n528: ```\n529: \n530: ### Incorrect Field Names\n531: \n532: ```yaml\n533: # BEFORE (wrong field names)\n534: ---\n535: Name: my-skill       # Should be lowercase\n536: desc: Description    # Should be 'description'\n537: tools: Read          # Should be 'allowed-tools'\n538: ---\n539: \n540: # AFTER (corrected)\n541: ---\n542: name: my-skill\n543: description: Description\n544: allowed-tools: Read\n545: ---\n546: ```\n547: \n548: ### Malformed Delimiters\n549: \n550: ```yaml\n551: # BEFORE (missing closing delimiter)\n552: ---\n553: name: my-skill\n554: description: Description\n555: allowed-tools: Read\n556: \n557: # Content starts here...\n558: \n559: # AFTER (delimiter added)\n560: ---\n561: name: my-skill\n562: description: Description\n563: allowed-tools: Read\n564: ---\n565: \n566: # Content starts here...\n567: ```\n568: \n569: ### Multiline Description Fix\n570: \n571: ```yaml\n572: # BEFORE (multiline - won't parse)\n573: ---\n574: name: my-skill\n575: description:\n576:   This is a long description\n577:   that spans multiple lines\n578: allowed-tools: Read\n579: ---\n580: \n581: # AFTER (single line)\n582: ---\n583: name: my-skill\n584: description: This is a long description that spans multiple lines\n585: allowed-tools: Read\n586: ---\n587: ```\n588: \n589: ### Remove from Knowledge File\n590: \n591: ```yaml\n592: # BEFORE (knowledge file with frontmatter)\n593: ---\n594: name: style-guide\n595: description: Documentation standards\n596: ---\n597: \n598: # Style Guide\n599: \n600: Content...\n601: \n602: # AFTER (frontmatter removed)\n603: # Style Guide\n604: \n605: Content...\n606: ```\n607: \n608: ---\n609: \n610: ## 7. AUTO-GENERATION GUIDELINES\n611: \n612: ### Field Inference Rules\n613: \n614: When auto-generating frontmatter, infer values from document content:\n615: \n616: **`name` Field**:\n617: ```\n618: Source: Parent directory name\n619: Method: Extract from file path\n620: \n621: Example:\n622:   Input: .opencode/skills/my-skill/SKILL.md\n623:   Output: my-skill\n624: ```\n625: \n626: **`description` Field**:\n627: ```\n628: Source: H1 subtitle or first paragraph\n629: Method: \n630:   1. Look for \" - \" in H1 (e.g., \"# Skill Name - Description\")\n631:   2. Fallback to first paragraph after H1\n632: \n633: Example:\n634:   H1: \"# My Skill - Brief description of purpose\"\n635:   Output: \"Brief description of purpose\"\n636: ```\n637: \n638: **`argument-hint` Field** (Commands):\n639: ```\n640: Source: INPUTS section or CONTRACT section\n641: Method: Extract from Required/Optional input lists\n642: \n643: Example:\n644:   Content:\n645:     ### Required Inputs\n646:     - `name`: Skill name\n647:     ### Optional Inputs  \n648:     - `version`: Version number\n649:   \n650:   Output: <name> [version]\n651: ```\n652: \n653: **`allowed-tools` Field**:\n654: ```\n655: Source: WORKFLOW section code examples\n656: Method: Extract tool names from code blocks\n657: \n658: Example:\n659:   Content:\n660:     ```\n661:     Read(\"file.md\")\n662:     Write(\"output.md\", content)\n663:     Bash(\"ls -la\")\n664:     ```\n665:   \n666:   Output: Read, Write, Bash\n667: ```\n668: \n669: ### Auto-Generation Decision Tree\n670: \n671: ```\n672: Document type detected?\n673: ├─► SKILL.md\n674: │   ├─ Has frontmatter? → Validate fields\n675: │   └─ Missing frontmatter? → Auto-generate + ask user to review\n676: │\n677: ├─► Command\n678: │   ├─ Has frontmatter? → Validate fields\n679: │   └─ Missing frontmatter? → Auto-generate from content\n680: │\n681: ├─► Knowledge\n682: │   ├─ Has frontmatter? → Remove it\n683: │   └─ No frontmatter? → Valid (no action)\n684: │\n685: ├─► Spec\n686: │   ├─ Has frontmatter? → Suggest removal\n687: │   └─ No frontmatter? → Valid (no action)\n688: │\n689: └─► README\n690:     ├─ In .opencode/skills/*/? → Optional skill-style\n691:     └─ Elsewhere? → No frontmatter needed\n692: ```\n693: \n694: ---\n695: \n696: ## 8. INTERACTIVE WORKFLOW\n697: \n698: ### Adding Frontmatter Interactively\n699: \n700: **Step 1: Present Inferred Template**\n701: ```\n702: STRUCTURAL FIX: Add YAML Frontmatter\n703: \n704: File: .opencode/skills/new-skill/SKILL.md\n705: Type: SKILL.md (frontmatter required)\n706: \n707: Proposed frontmatter (inferred from document):\n708: ---\n709: name: new-skill\n710: description: Brief description inferred from H1 subtitle\n711: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Bash\n712: ---\n713: \n714: Options:\n715: 1. Accept as-is\n716: 2. Edit values before applying\n717: 3. Skip (leave non-compliant)\n718: \n719: Choice:\n720: ```\n721: \n722: **Step 2: Edit Values (if selected)**\n723: ```\n724: Edit frontmatter values:\n725: \n726: name [new-skill]: _\n727: description [Brief description...]: _\n728: allowed-tools [Read, Write, Bash]: _\n729: \n730: Press Enter to keep default, or type new value.\n731: ```\n732: \n733: **Step 3: Apply**\n734: ```bash\n735: # Insert at beginning of file\n736: {\n737:   echo \"---\"\n738:   echo \"name: $name\"\n739:   echo \"description: $description\"\n740:   echo \"allowed-tools: $allowed_tools\"\n741:   echo \"---\"\n742:   echo \"\"\n743:   cat original_file.md\n744: } > updated_file.md\n745: ```\n746: \n747: ---\n748: \n749: ## 9. BEST PRACTICES SUMMARY\n750: \n751: ### DO\n752: \n753: | Practice | Reason |\n754: |----------|--------|\n755: | Keep description on single line | Parser limitation |\n756: | Match `name` to directory name | Consistency, discoverability |\n757: | Order tools by frequency | Most used first |\n758: | Use exact tool names | Case-sensitive matching |\n759: | Validate before committing | Catch errors early |\n760: \n761: ### DON'T\n762: \n763: | Anti-Pattern | Problem |\n764: |--------------|---------|\n765: | Multiline descriptions | Won't parse correctly |\n766: | Uppercase in `name` | Violates format requirement |\n767: | Frontmatter on knowledge files | Implies programmatic interface |\n768: | Empty required fields | Validation failure |\n769: | Made-up tool names | Tools won't be available |\n770: \n771: ---\n772: \n773: ## 10. QUICK REFERENCE\n774: \n775: ### Frontmatter Decision Tree\n776: \n777: ```\n778: Document type?\n779: ├─► SKILL.md       → MUST have: name, description, allowed-tools\n780: ├─► Command        → MUST have: description, argument-hint, allowed-tools\n781: ├─► Knowledge      → MUST NOT have frontmatter (remove if present)\n782: ├─► Spec           → SHOULD NOT have frontmatter (use inline metadata)\n783: └─► README         → No requirement (usually none)\n784: ```\n785: \n786: ### Field Requirements Matrix\n787: \n788: | Document Type | name | description | argument-hint | allowed-tools |\n789: |---------------|------|-------------|---------------|---------------|\n790: | **SKILL.md** | ✅ Required | ✅ Required | ❌ N/A | ✅ Required |\n791: | **Command** | ⚪ Optional | ✅ Required | ✅ Required | ✅ Required |\n792: | **Knowledge** | ❌ Forbidden | ❌ Forbidden | ❌ Forbidden | ❌ Forbidden |\n793: | **Spec** | ❌ Not used | ❌ Not used | ❌ Not used | ❌ Not used |\n794: \n795: ### Common Mistakes\n796: \n797: | Mistake | Fix |\n798: |---------|-----|\n799: | Knowledge file with frontmatter | Remove frontmatter |\n800: | SKILL.md missing `name` | Add with directory name |\n801: | Command missing `argument-hint` | Infer from content or ask |\n802: | Spec with YAML frontmatter | Convert to inline metadata |\n803: | Wrong field names (Name vs name) | Use lowercase field names |\n804: | Multiline description | Collapse to single line |\n805: \n806: ---\n807: \n808: ## 11. RELATED RESOURCES\n809: \n810: ### Templates\n811: - [skill_md_template.md](../skill/skill_md_template.md) - SKILL.md file templates\n812: - [command_template.md](../command_template.md) - Command file templates\n813: \n814: ### Standards\n815: - [core_standards.md](../../references/global/core_standards.md) - Document type rules\n816: - [validation.md](../../references/global/validation.md) - Quality scoring\n\n(End of file - total 816 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: YAML Frontmatter Templates\ndescription: Templates and validation rules for YAML frontmatter across all document types in the OpenCode ecosystem.\n---\n\n# YAML Frontmatter Templates - Document Type Reference\n\nTemplates and validation rules for YAML frontmatter by document type.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### What Is YAML Frontmatter?\n\n**YAML frontmatter** is a metadata block at the beginning of markdown files, delimited by `---` markers. It provides machine-readable configuration that controls how AI agents and tools process the document.\n\n```yaml\n---\nname: skill-name","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/frontmatter_templates.md","time":{"start":1780204908121,"end":1780204908137}},"id":"prt_e7c7b2c85002ikkuZzGS7As1Hm","sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","messageID":"msg_e7c7b211d0016iIzc4TTGX6KPL"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780204908392,"sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","part":{"id":"prt_e7c7b2f67001FsW1hTu861pe8L","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"7db0c07b7b115acbc854af1e0d90ac1e9a51eb99","messageID":"msg_e7c7b211d0016iIzc4TTGX6KPL","sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":60542,"input":428,"output":81,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":1871,"read":58162}},"cost":0.004642545}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780204915134,"sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","part":{"id":"prt_e7c7b49b9001ZUrT3j7GbtnOTH","messageID":"msg_e7c7b3054001i9VsPvsC4VPC8C","sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","snapshot":"60e25971940d768041e7effb87042af167316e5d","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780204917192,"sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_19r2rkccprrx_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Skill Reference File Templates\n3: description: Comprehensive templates for creating effective reference files for AI agent skills with workflows, decision logic, and validation checkpoints.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Skill Reference File Templates - AI Agent Skills\n7: \n8: Templates for creating reference files in AI agent skills with deep-dive technical guidance.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n13: \n14: ### Location & Naming\n15: \n16: **Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/references/`\n17: \n18: **Naming Convention:** snake_case with `.md` extension only\n19: \n20: | ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |\n21: |---------------|-----------------|\n22: | `implementation_workflows.md` | `ImplementationWorkflows.md` (PascalCase) |\n23: | `tool_catalog.md` | `tool-catalog.md` (kebab-case) |\n24: | `debugging_guide.md` | `DebuggingGuide.MD` (wrong case) |\n25: | `quick_reference.md` | `quickReference.md` (camelCase) |\n26: | `code_quality_standards.md` | `code quality standards.md` (spaces) |\n27: \n28: ### When to Create References\n29: \n30: **Create a reference file when:**\n31: - Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n32: - Decision trees with multiple branches\n33: - Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n34: - Systematic debugging procedures\n35: - Tool integration details\n36: - Content exceeds 200 lines\n37: \n38: **Keep in SKILL.md when:**\n39: - Content under 200 lines\n40: - Simple workflows (3-5 steps)\n41: - Overview and \"When to Use\" sections\n42: - Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n43: \n44: ---\n45: \n46: ## 2. DOCUMENT STRUCTURE\n47: \n48: ### Document Structure: Title and Intro\n49: \n50: **CRITICAL: The intro after the H1 title must be 1-2 SHORT sentences only.**\n51: \n52: ```markdown\n53: ---\n54: title: [Title]\n55: description: [One-line description - same as intro]\n56: ---\n57: \n58: # [Title]\n59: \n60: [1-2 SHORT sentences only. Brief hook/summary. NO subsections, NO headers here.]\n61: \n62: ---\n63: \n64: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n65: [All detailed content goes here, NOT in the intro]\n66: \n67: ```\n68: \n69: > **WARNING: DO NOT duplicate content between intro and Section 1.**\n70: > The intro is a hook; Section 1 provides the details.\n71: \n72: #### GOOD Intro Structure\n73: \n74: ```markdown\n75: # Git Commit Workflows\n76: \n77: Step-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n78: \n79: ---\n80: \n81: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n82: \n83: ### Purpose\n84: Provides systematic workflows for analyzing changes, filtering artifacts, and creating well-structured commits.\n85: \n86: ### When to Use\n87: - Creating commits with multiple file changes\n88: - Filtering generated files from commits\n89: - Writing clear commit messages\n90: \n91: ### Core Principle\n92: Atomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n93: ```\n94: \n95: #### BAD Intro Structure (duplicates content)\n96: \n97: ```markdown\n98: # Git Commit Workflows\n99: \n100: Step-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n101: \n102: ### Core Principle   ← WRONG: No headers in intro!\n103: Atomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n104: \n105: ### When to Use      ← WRONG: This belongs in Section 1!\n106: - Creating commits with multiple file changes\n107: \n108: ---\n109: \n110: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n111: \n112: ### Purpose\n113: Provides systematic workflows...  ← Now this duplicates the intro!\n114: \n115: ### Core Principle\n116: Atomic commits...  ← DUPLICATED from intro!\n117: ```\n118: \n119: #### Intro vs Section 1 Content Placement\n120: \n121: | Content Type          | Intro (after H1) | Section 1 OVERVIEW |\n122: | --------------------- | ---------------- | ------------------ |\n123: | 1-2 sentence summary  | ✅ YES            | ❌ NO (don't repeat) |\n124: | Core Principle        | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n125: | When to Use           | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n126: | Primary Sources       | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (as \"Key Sources\") |\n127: | Purpose (detailed)    | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n128: | Prerequisites         | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n129: | Any H3 subsections    | ❌ NEVER          | ✅ YES              |\n130: \n131: ---\n132: \n133: ### What Are AI Agent Skill Reference Files?\n134: \n135: Reference files are detailed technical documentation in the `references/` directory that provide deep-dive guidance with **explicit reasoning** - making thought processes visible, showing decision logic, and analyzing root causes.\n136: \n137: **Core Purpose**:\n138: - **Technical depth** - Step-by-step reasoning with rationale\n139: - **Phased workflows** - Structured processes with validation checkpoints\n140: - **Pattern libraries** - Before/after examples, comparison tables\n141: - **Tool integration** - MCP tools, scripts, asset references\n142: - **Root cause analysis** - Systematic debugging and troubleshooting\n143: \n144: **Key Difference from Generic Documentation**:\n145: - AI agent skills = Actionable workflows with explicit reasoning\n146: - Generic docs = Information reference without decision logic\n147: \n148: ### Progressive Disclosure in Skills\n149: \n150: ```\n151: Level 1: Metadata (name + description)\n152:          └─ Always in context (~100 words)\n153:             ↓\n154: Level 2: SKILL.md body\n155:          └─ When skill triggers (<5k words)\n156:             ↓\n157: Level 3: Reference files (this document)\n158:          └─ Loaded as needed (500-3000 lines per file)\n159: ```\n160: \n161: **Reference files = Level 3**: Deep technical guidance loaded only when the agent needs specific workflow details.\n162: \n163: ---\n164: \n165: ## 3. WHEN TO CREATE REFERENCE FILES\n166: \n167: ### Create Reference File When\n168: \n169: **Workflow Complexity**:\n170: - Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n171: - Decision trees with multiple branches\n172: - Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n173: - Systematic debugging procedures\n174: \n175: **Technical Depth**:\n176: - Root cause analysis required\n177: - Tool integration details (MCP, scripts)\n178: - Before/after code transformations\n179: - Common error patterns and fixes\n180: \n181: **Size Threshold**:\n182: - Content exceeds 200 lines\n183: - Multiple related workflows\n184: - Extensive troubleshooting needed\n185: \n186: ### Keep in SKILL.md When\n187: \n188: **Core Content**:\n189: - Overview and \"When to Use\"\n190: - High-level workflow (3-5 steps)\n191: - Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n192:   > **Note**: RULES sections in SKILL.md use ALL-CAPS H3 headers: `### ALWAYS`, `### NEVER`, `### ESCALATE IF` (or `####` at phase depth). See [skill_md_template.md](./skill_md_template.md) for the complete pattern.\n193: - Quick reference\n194: \n195: **Size**: Content under 200 lines\n196: \n197: ### Reference File Types for AI Agent Skills\n198: \n199: | Type                | Purpose                                | Example (snake_case)          | Size           |\n200: | ------------------- | -------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- | -------------- |\n201: | **Workflow**        | Multi-phase processes with checkpoints | `implementation_workflows.md` | 500-1500 lines |\n202: | **Pattern Library** | Code patterns with before/after        | `shared_patterns.md`          | 300-800 lines  |\n203: | **Standards**       | Rules and conventions                  | `code_quality_standards.md`   | 400-1000 lines |\n204: | **Debugging**       | Systematic troubleshooting             | `debugging_workflows.md`      | 600-1200 lines |\n205: | **Tool Guide**      | MCP/external tool integration          | `devtools_guide.md`           | 200-600 lines  |\n206: | **Quick Reference** | Commands, shortcuts, checklists        | `quick_reference.md`          | 200-400 lines  |\n207: \n208: **Note:** All reference file names use snake_case (underscores, lowercase).\n209: \n210: ---\n211: \n212: ## 4. AI AGENT SKILL REFERENCE CHARACTERISTICS\n213: \n214: ### Core Principle Statements\n215: \n216: **Purpose**: Distill philosophy into one-line wisdom\n217: \n218: > **PLACEMENT**: Core Principle goes in **Section 1 OVERVIEW**, NOT in the intro paragraph after the H1 title.\n219: \n220: **Format**:\n221: ```markdown\n222: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n223: \n224: ### Core Principle\n225: \n226: [Single powerful statement that captures the workflow's essence]\n227: ```\n228: \n229: **Examples from Real Skills**:\n230: - \"Wait for the actual condition you care about, not a guess about how long it takes\"\n231: - \"ALWAYS find root cause before attempting fixes. Symptom fixes are failure\"\n232: - \"Atomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history\"\n233: \n234: ### Phased Workflows with Validation\n235: \n236: **Purpose**: Structured processes with mandatory checkpoints\n237: \n238: **Format**:\n239: ```markdown\n240: ### The [Number] Phases\n241: \n242: You MUST complete each phase before proceeding to the next.\n243: \n244: #### Phase 1: [Phase Name]\n245: \n246: **Purpose**: [What this phase accomplishes]\n247: \n248: **Actions**:\n249: 1. [Action 1]\n250: 2. [Action 2]\n251: \n252: **Validation**: `checkpoint_name`\n253: \n254: #### Phase 2: [Phase Name]\n255: \n256: [Similar structure]\n257: ```\n258: \n259: **Key Elements**:\n260: - **\"You MUST complete\"** - Mandatory language\n261: - **Named checkpoints** - `checkpoint_name` for validation\n262: - **Sequential phases** - Cannot skip ahead\n263: \n264: ### Before/After Code Examples\n265: \n266: **Purpose**: Show transformation from wrong to right\n267: \n268: **Format**:\n269: ```markdown\n270: ### [Pattern Name]\n271: \n272: **BEFORE**: [Problem description]\n273: \\```[language]\n274: // Bad code with issues\n275: // Showing what NOT to do\n276: \\```\n277: \n278: **AFTER**: [Solution description]\n279: \\```[language]\n280: // Good code with fixes\n281: // Showing correct approach\n282: \\```\n283: \n284: **Why better**: [Explanation of improvement]\n285: ```\n286: \n287: **Key Elements**:\n288: - `BEFORE:` marker for the wrong-way code\n289: - `AFTER:` marker for the right-way code\n290: - Inline comments explaining issues\n291: - \"Why better\" rationale\n292: \n293: ### Pattern Comparison Tables\n294: \n295: **Purpose**: Compare approaches across scenarios\n296: \n297: **Format**:\n298: ```markdown\n299: ### Common Patterns\n300: \n301: | Scenario     | Approach A (Wrong) | Approach B (Right) | Why Better  |\n302: | ------------ | ------------------ | ------------------ | ----------- |\n303: | [Scenario 1] | [Wrong way]        | [Right way]        | [Rationale] |\n304: | [Scenario 2] | [Wrong way]        | [Right way]        | [Rationale] |\n305: ```\n306: \n307: **Use when**: Multiple scenarios need comparison\n308: \n309: ### Decision Logic in Markdown\n310: \n311: **Purpose**: Explicit if/then logic for workflow decisions\n312: \n313: **Format**:\n314: \\```markdown\n315: ### Decision Logic\n316: \n317: \\```markdown\n318: IF [condition A]:\n319:   → [Action/Path A]\n320:   → [Expected outcome A]\n321: \n322: IF [condition B]:\n323:   → [Action/Path B]\n324:   → [Expected outcome B]\n325: \n326: IF [condition C]:\n327:   → [Action/Path C]\n328:   → [Expected outcome C]\n329: \\```\n330: \\```\n331: \n332: **Alternative format** (decision tree):\n333: \\```markdown\n334: \\```\n335: Analyze situation\n336: ├─ Condition A met\n337: │  └─ Execute Workflow A\n338: │     └─ Expected outcome A\n339: ├─ Condition B met\n340: │  └─ Execute Workflow B\n341: │     └─ Expected outcome B\n342: └─ Condition C met\n343:    └─ Execute Workflow C\n344:       └─ Expected outcome C\n345: \\```\n346: \\```\n347: \n348: ### Validation Checkpoints\n349: \n350: **Purpose**: Named checkpoints throughout workflows\n351: \n352: **Format**:\n353: ```markdown\n354: **Validation**: `checkpoint_name`\n355: ```\n356: \n357: **Examples**:\n358: - `files_analyzed`\n359: - `artifacts_filtered`\n360: - `strategy_determined`\n361: - `root_cause_identified`\n362: \n363: **Usage**: Reference in quality checklists and debugging\n364: \n365: ### Prerequisites Section\n366: \n367: **Purpose**: Link to required standards and context\n368: \n369: > **PLACEMENT**: Prerequisites go in **Section 1 OVERVIEW**, NOT in the intro paragraph.\n370: \n371: **Format**:\n372: ```markdown\n373: # [Workflow Name]\n374: \n375: [1-2 sentence summary only - no prerequisites here]\n376: \n377: ---\n378: \n379: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n380: \n381: ### Prerequisites\n382: Follow [standard name] for all implementations:\n383: - **[Standard 1]**: [Brief description]\n384: - **[Standard 2]**: [Brief description]\n385: - See [standard_file.md](./standard_file.md) for complete requirements\n386: ```\n387: \n388: **Key Elements**:\n389: - Appears in Section 1 OVERVIEW, not intro\n390: - Links to other reference files\n391: - Lists specific requirements\n392: \n393: ### Tool Integration References\n394: \n395: **Purpose**: Show MCP tool usage, script execution, asset references\n396: \n397: **Format for MCP Tools**:\n398: \\```markdown\n399: **Automated [Task] via MCP:**\n400: \n401: Instead of [manual approach], use Chrome DevTools MCP:\n402: \n403: \\```markdown\n404: 1. [Step 1]:\n405:    [Use tool: mcp__chrome_devtools__tool_name]\n406:    - parameter1: \"value\"\n407:    - parameter2: value\n408: \n409: 2. [Step 2]:\n410:    [Use tool: mcp__chrome_devtools__tool_name]\n411: \\```\n412: \n413: **What you'll see:**\n414: - [Expected output 1]\n415: - [Expected output 2]\n416: \n417: **Example output:**\n418: \\```json\n419: {\n420:   \"field\": \"value\",\n421:   \"data\": \"example\"\n422: }\n423: \\```\n424: \\```\n425: \n426: **Format for Scripts**:\n427: ```markdown\n428: **See also:** [script_name.js](../scripts/script_name.js) for production-ready implementation\n429: ```\n430: \n431: **Format for Assets**:\n432: ```markdown\n433: **See also:** [template_name.md](../assets/template_name.md) for complete templates\n434: ```\n435: \n436: ### Common Error Patterns\n437: \n438: **Purpose**: Document actual errors with explanations\n439: \n440: **Format**:\n441: \\```markdown\n442: **Common [System/Browser] Errors:**\n443: \n444: \\```javascript\n445: // [Actual error message]\n446: // → [What it means]\n447: // → [How to fix]\n448: \n449: // [Another error message]\n450: // → [What it means]\n451: // → [How to fix]\n452: \\```\n453: \\```\n454: \n455: **Example**:\n456: \\```markdown\n457: **Common Browser Errors:**\n458: \n459: \\```javascript\n460: // Uncaught TypeError: Cannot read property 'X' of undefined\n461: // → Variable is undefined, check initialization\n462: // → Verify element exists before accessing properties\n463: \n464: // Failed to load resource: net::ERR_BLOCKED_BY_CLIENT\n465: // → Ad blocker or browser extension blocking resource\n466: // → Check Network tab, test with extensions disabled\n467: \\```\n468: \\```\n469: \n470: ### Scope Limitations\n471: \n472: **Purpose**: Explicitly state what's in/out of scope\n473: \n474: **Format**:\n475: ```markdown\n476: **Note:** [Clarification of what IS supported]\n477: \n478: **Out of scope:** [What is NOT supported]\n479: ```\n480: \n481: **Example**:\n482: ```markdown\n483: **Note:** All browser testing done via Chrome DevTools MCP.\n484: \n485: **Out of scope:** Cross-browser testing in Firefox, Safari (MCP is Chrome-only)\n486: ```\n487: \n488: ### Browser Testing Checklists\n489: \n490: **Purpose**: Specific viewport tests with checkboxes\n491: \n492: **Format**:\n493: \\```markdown\n494: **Browser Testing Checklist:**\n495: \n496: \\```markdown\n497: □ Chrome (via Chrome DevTools MCP)\n498: □ Mobile viewport (375px) - use DevTools emulation\n499: □ Tablet viewport (768px) - use DevTools emulation\n500: □ Desktop viewport (1920px)\n501: □ Test viewport transitions (320px, 768px, 1920px)\n502: \\```\n503: \\```\n504: \n505: ---\n506: \n507: ### Phased Workflow with Checkpoints Example\n508: \n509: **Purpose**: Show complete workflow with validation gates\n510: \n511: **Format**:\n512: ```yaml\n513: implementation_workflow:\n514:   phase_1_preparation:\n515:     purpose: \"Gather context and analyze requirements\"\n516:     actions:\n517:       - \"Read user request carefully\"\n518:       - \"Identify affected files and systems\"\n519:       - \"Review relevant documentation\"\n520:     checkpoint: \"requirements_understood\"\n521:     validation_questions:\n522:       - \"Can I clearly explain what needs to be done?\"\n523:       - \"Do I know which files will change?\"\n524:       - \"Are there any unclear requirements?\"\n525: \n526:   phase_2_design:\n527:     purpose: \"Plan the implementation approach\"\n528:     depends_on: \"phase_1_preparation\"\n529:     actions:\n530:       - \"Choose simplest solution that works\"\n531:       - \"Identify potential edge cases\"\n532:       - \"Plan validation strategy\"\n533:     checkpoint: \"design_approved\"\n534:     validation_questions:\n535:       - \"Is this the simplest approach?\"\n536:       - \"Have I considered edge cases?\"\n537:       - \"Can I test this effectively?\"\n538: \n539:   phase_3_implementation:\n540:     purpose: \"Execute the planned changes\"\n541:     depends_on: \"phase_2_design\"\n542:     actions:\n543:       - \"Make code changes following standards\"\n544:       - \"Add necessary tests\"\n545:       - \"Update documentation\"\n546:     checkpoint: \"changes_complete\"\n547:     validation_questions:\n548:       - \"Do all tests pass?\"\n549:       - \"Is code documented?\"\n550:       - \"Are standards followed?\"\n551: \n552:   phase_4_validation:\n553:     purpose: \"Verify correctness and quality\"\n554:     depends_on: \"phase_3_implementation\"\n555:     actions:\n556:       - \"Run full test suite\"\n557:       - \"Check code quality metrics\"\n558:       - \"Review against requirements\"\n559:     checkpoint: \"quality_verified\"\n560:     validation_questions:\n561:       - \"Do all tests pass?\"\n562:       - \"Are quality metrics met?\"\n563:       - \"Does this satisfy the original request?\"\n564: ```\n565: \n566: **Example in Markdown Reference**:\n567: ```markdown\n568: ### Implementation Workflow\n569: \n570: You MUST complete each phase before proceeding to the next.\n571: \n572: #### Phase 1: Preparation\n573: \n574: **Purpose**: Gather context and analyze requirements\n575: \n576: **Actions**:\n577: 1. Read user request carefully\n578: 2. Identify affected files and systems\n579: 3. Review relevant documentation\n580: \n581: **Validation**: `requirements_understood`\n582: - Can I clearly explain what needs to be done?\n583: - Do I know which files will change?\n584: - Are there any unclear requirements?\n585: \n586: #### Phase 2: Design\n587: \n588: **Purpose**: Plan the implementation approach\n589: \n590: **Actions**:\n591: 1. Choose simplest solution that works\n592: 2. Identify potential edge cases\n593: 3. Plan validation strategy\n594: \n595: **Validation**: `design_approved`\n596: - Is this the simplest approach?\n597: - Have I considered edge cases?\n598: - Can I test this effectively?\n599: \n600: [Continue with remaining phases...]\n601: ```\n602: \n603: ---\n604: \n605: ## 5. CONVERTING LOGIC TO EXECUTABLE CODE\n606: \n607: ### When to Extract Logic from Markdown\n608: \n609: **Purpose**: Separate documentation from executable code for better maintainability, testability, and reusability.\n610: \n611: **Decision Criteria**:\n612: \n613: | Pattern Type          | Keep in Markdown  | Extract to Code           | Reasoning                                    |\n614: | --------------------- | ----------------- | ------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- |\n615: | **Python functions**  | ❌ No              | ✅ Yes → `/scripts/*.py`   | Type safety, unit testing, reusability       |\n616: | **YAML configs**      | ❌ No              | ✅ Yes → `/assets/*.yaml`  | Dynamic loading, version control, validation |\n617: | **Decision trees**    | ⚠️ High-level only | ✅ Details → YAML + Python | Machine-readable, can be validated           |\n618: | **Command mappings**  | ⚠️ Examples only   | ✅ Full map → YAML         | Easier maintenance, can be imported          |\n619: | **Workflow diagrams** | ✅ Yes (generated) | ✅ Source → YAML           | YAML = source of truth, diagram = output     |\n620: | **Checklists**        | ✅ Yes             | ❌ No                      | Human-readable is primary use case           |\n621: | **Before/after code** | ✅ Yes             | ❌ No                      | Educational, not executable                  |\n622: \n623: ### Extraction Pattern\n624: \n625: **In Markdown (Reference File)**:\n626: ```markdown\n627: ### [Workflow Name]\n628: \n629: [High-level description of what the workflow does]\n630: \n631: **Implementation:** See [workflow_name.py](../scripts/workflow_name.py) for execution logic and [workflow_config.yaml](../assets/workflow_config.yaml) for configuration.\n632: \n633: **Quick Overview**:\n634: 1. [Step 1 - high level]\n635: 2. [Step 2 - high level]\n636: 3. [Step 3 - high level]\n637: \n638: **Configuration Options:**\n639: - See YAML config for customizable parameters\n640: - Default values optimized for common use cases\n641: ```\n642: \n643: ### Benefits of Separation\n644: \n645: - **Type safety** - Python type hints catch errors at development time\n646: - **Testability** - Unit tests for logic, integration tests for workflows\n647: - **Reusability** - Imported by multiple skills or scripts\n648: - **Version control** - Git diffs show logic changes clearly\n649: - **Schema validation** - YAML can be validated against schemas\n650: - **Dynamic loading** - Configuration changes without code edits\n651: \n652: ### Example: Mode Detection Extraction\n653: \n654: **❌ BEFORE** (inline Python in markdown):\n655: \\```python\n656: def detect_mode(request):\n657:     if '$quick' in request: return 'quick', 5\n658:     elif '$ticket' in request: return 'ticket', 10\n659:     return 'interactive', 10\n660: \\```\n661: \n662: **✅ AFTER** (extracted with type safety):\n663: \n664: `/scripts/mode_detection.py`:\n665: \\```python\n666: from dataclasses import dataclass\n667: \n668: @dataclass\n669: class ModeConfig:\n670:     mode: str\n671:     depth_rounds: int\n672: \n673: def detect_mode(request: str) -> ModeConfig:\n674:     \"\"\"Detect mode from command shortcuts.\"\"\"\n675:     if '$quick' in request:\n676:         return ModeConfig('quick', 5)\n677:     elif '$ticket' in request:\n678:         return ModeConfig('ticket', 10)\n679:     return ModeConfig('interactive', 10)\n680: \\```\n681: \n682: `/tests/test_mode_detection.py`:\n683: \\```python\n684: def test_quick_mode():\n685:     assert detect_mode(\"$quick fix\").mode == 'quick'\n686: \\```\n687: \n688: **Why better:** Type hints, testable, reusable, separated from docs\n689: \n690: ---\n691: \n692: ## 6. YAML CONFIGURATION PATTERNS\n693: \n694: ### Purpose\n695: \n696: **YAML for configuration data** - Separate configuration from documentation for easier maintenance and dynamic loading.\n697: \n698: **When to use YAML**:\n699: - Configuration data (thresholds, mappings, rules)\n700: - Data structures (nested objects, lists)\n701: - Workflow definitions (step sequences, pipelines)\n702: - Decision trees (conditional logic patterns)\n703: - Validation schemas\n704: \n705: ### Standard YAML Structure\n706: \n707: ```yaml\n708: # [config_name].yaml\n709: metadata:\n710:   version: \"1.0.0\"\n711:   description: \"Configuration for [feature name]\"\n712: \n713: config:\n714:   threshold_values:\n715:     low: 1\n716:     medium: 5\n717:     high: 10\n718:   feature_flags:\n719:     enable_feature_x: true\n720:   mappings:\n721:     $quick: \"quick_mode\"\n722:     $ticket: \"ticket_mode\"\n723: ```\n724: \n725: ### File Organization\n726: \n727: ```\n728: .opencode/skills/[skill-name]/\n729: ├── assets/\n730: │   ├── workflow_configs/\n731: │   │   ├── canvas_methodology.yaml\n732: │   │   ├── variant_detection.yaml\n733: │   │   └── complexity_scoring.yaml\n734: │   ├── mappings/\n735: │   │   ├── command_mappings.yaml\n736: │   │   ├── mode_recognition.yaml\n737: │   │   └── shortcut_definitions.yaml\n738: │   └── templates/\n739: │       └── [template files]\n740: ```\n741: \n742: ### Loading Pattern (Python)\n743: \n744: ```python\n745: import yaml\n746: from pathlib import Path\n747: \n748: def load_config(config_name: str) -> dict:\n749:     \"\"\"Load YAML config from assets directory.\"\"\"\n750:     config_path = Path(__file__).parent.parent / f\"assets/{config_name}.yaml\"\n751:     with open(config_path) as f:\n752:         return yaml.safe_load(f)['config']\n753: \n754: # Usage\n755: config = load_config(\"canvas_methodology\")\n756: ```\n757: \n758: ### Example: Variant Detection Rules\n759: \n760: **❌ BEFORE** (markdown table):\n761: ```markdown\n762: | Trigger                    | Action             |\n763: | -------------------------- | ------------------ |\n764: | \"show options\"             | Offer 3-5 variants |\n765: | Complexity 7+ + \"not sure\" | Offer variants     |\n766: ```\n767: \n768: **✅ AFTER** (YAML + Python):\n769: \n770: `/assets/variant_detection_rules.yaml`:\n771: ```yaml\n772: config:\n773:   variant_triggers:\n774:     explicit_keywords: [\"show me options\", \"variations\"]\n775:     implicit:\n776:       complexity_threshold: 7\n777:       uncertainty_signals: [\"not sure\", \"what would work\"]\n778:   variant_count:\n779:     simple: [2, 3]\n780:     complex: [5, 10]\n781: ```\n782: \n783: `/scripts/variant_detector.py`:\n784: ```python\n785: import yaml\n786: \n787: class VariantDetector:\n788:     def __init__(self, config_path: str):\n789:         with open(config_path) as f:\n790:             self.config = yaml.safe_load(f)['config']\n791: \n792:     def should_generate_variants(self, request: str, complexity: int) -> bool:\n793:         keywords = self.config['variant_triggers']['explicit_keywords']\n794:         if any(kw in request.lower() for kw in keywords):\n795:             return True\n796: \n797:         threshold = self.config['variant_triggers']['implicit']['complexity_threshold']\n798:         if complexity >= threshold:\n799:             signals = self.config['variant_triggers']['implicit']['uncertainty_signals']\n800:             return any(s in request.lower() for s in signals)\n801:         return False\n802: ```\n803: \n804: **Why better:** Dynamic config loading, easier maintenance, schema validation possible\n805: \n806: ---\n807: \n808: ## 7. PYTHON SCRIPT INTEGRATION\n809: \n810: ### When to Use Python for Logic\n811: \n812: **Use Python scripts when**:\n813: - Procedural logic (workflows, algorithms)\n814: - Complex conditionals (multi-step decisions)\n815: - Data transformation (processing, validation)\n816: - API integration (external services)\n817: - File operations (reading, parsing, generating)\n818: \n819: ### Type Hints and Docstring Standards\n820: \n821: **Always include**:\n822: - Type hints for parameters and return values\n823: - Google-style docstrings (Args, Returns, Raises, Examples)\n824: - Dataclasses for structured data\n825: \n826: **Example**:\n827: ```python\n828: from dataclasses import dataclass\n829: from pathlib import Path\n830: \n831: @dataclass\n832: class ValidationResult:\n833:     is_valid: bool\n834:     errors: list[str]\n835: \n836: def validate_config(config_path: Path) -> ValidationResult:\n837:     \"\"\"\n838:     Validate configuration file.\n839: \n840:     Args:\n841:         config_path: Path to YAML config file\n842: \n843:     Returns:\n844:         ValidationResult with status and errors\n845: \n846:     Raises:\n847:         FileNotFoundError: If config doesn't exist\n848:     \"\"\"\n849:     if not config_path.exists():\n850:         raise FileNotFoundError(f\"Config not found: {config_path}\")\n851:     # Validation logic\n852:     return ValidationResult(is_valid=True, errors=[])\n853: ```\n854: \n855: ### Unit Testing Requirements\n856: \n857: **Every Python script must have tests**:\n858: - Naming: `test_[script_name].py` in `/tests/` directory\n859: - Coverage: ≥80% line coverage\n860: - Framework: pytest\n861: \n862: **Example**:\n863: ```python\n864: import pytest\n865: from scripts.config_validator import validate_config\n866: \n867: def test_validate_success(tmp_path):\n868:     config = tmp_path / \"config.yaml\"\n869:     config.write_text(\"config:\\n  threshold: 5\")\n870:     result = validate_config(config)\n871:     assert result.is_valid\n872: \n873: def test_validate_missing_file():\n874:     with pytest.raises(FileNotFoundError):\n875:         validate_config(Path(\"nonexistent.yaml\"))\n876: ```\n877: \n878: ### Import and Reference Patterns\n879: \n880: **Python import order**: Standard library → Third-party → Local\n881: \n882: **Markdown references**:\n883: ```markdown\n884: **See also:** [script_name.py](../scripts/script_name.py), [config.yaml](../assets/config.yaml)\n885: ```\n886: \n887: ### Example: Workflow Decision Logic\n888: \n889: **❌ BEFORE** (text decision tree):\n890: ```markdown\n891: IF \"$quick\": use quick mode (5 rounds)\n892: IF \"$ticket\": use ticket mode (10 rounds)\n893: OTHERWISE: use interactive mode\n894: ```\n895: \n896: **✅ AFTER** (Python with type safety):\n897: \n898: `/scripts/workflow_router.py`:\n899: ```python\n900: from typing import Literal\n901: from dataclasses import dataclass\n902: \n903: WorkflowMode = Literal[\"quick\", \"ticket\", \"interactive\"]\n904: \n905: @dataclass\n906: class WorkflowDecision:\n907:     mode: WorkflowMode\n908:     depth_rounds: int\n909: \n910: def route_workflow(request: str) -> WorkflowDecision:\n911:     \"\"\"Route request to appropriate workflow.\"\"\"\n912:     if '$quick' in request.lower():\n913:         return WorkflowDecision(\"quick\", 5)\n914:     if '$ticket' in request.lower():\n915:         return WorkflowDecision(\"ticket\", 10)\n916:     return WorkflowDecision(\"interactive\", 10)\n917: ```\n918: \n919: `/tests/test_workflow_router.py`:\n920: ```python\n921: def test_quick_mode():\n922:     assert route_workflow(\"$quick fix\").mode == \"quick\"\n923: \n924: def test_default_mode():\n925:     assert route_workflow(\"help me\").mode == \"interactive\"\n926: ```\n927: \n928: **Why better:** Type-safe with Literal, testable, structured with dataclass\n929: \n930: ---\n931: \n932: ## 8. STANDARD STRUCTURE TEMPLATE\n933: \n934: ### Complete Skill Directory Structure\n935: \n936: **Path:** `.opencode/skills/` (singular, not `skills` or `openskills`)\n937: \n938: ```\n939: .opencode/skills/[skill-name]/\n940: ├── SKILL.md                    # Main skill file (Level 2 in progressive disclosure)\n941: ├── references/                 # Deep-dive technical documentation (Level 3)\n942: │   ├── workflow_name.md        # Multi-phase workflows with checkpoints (snake_case)\n943: │   ├── patterns_library.md     # Before/after code patterns (snake_case)\n944: │   ├── debugging_guide.md      # Systematic troubleshooting (snake_case)\n945: │   └── quick_reference.md      # Commands, shortcuts, checklists (snake_case)\n946: ├── scripts/                    # Executable Python logic\n947: │   ├── mode_detection.py       # Procedural logic, algorithms\n948: │   ├── workflow_router.py      # Decision logic\n949: │   ├── config_validator.py     # Data transformation\n950: │   └── __init__.py             # Package initialization\n951: ├── assets/                     # Configuration and data files\n952: │   ├── workflow_configs/       # YAML workflow definitions\n953: │   │   ├── canvas_methodology.yaml\n954: │   │   └── complexity_scoring.yaml\n955: │   ├── mappings/               # YAML mapping data\n956: │   │   ├── command_mappings.yaml\n957: │   │   └── mode_recognition.yaml\n958: │   └── templates/              # Markdown/code templates\n959: │       ├── template_name.md\n960: │       └── component_template.tsx\n961: └── tests/                      # Unit and integration tests\n962:     ├── test_mode_detection.py\n963:     ├── test_workflow_router.py\n964:     ├── test_config_validator.py\n965:     └── __init__.py\n966: ```\n967: \n968: ### Directory Purposes\n969: \n970: **SKILL.md** (Required): Overview, workflow (3-5 steps), rules. Target: <200 lines\n971: \n972: **references/** (Optional): Detailed workflows, patterns, debugging. Target: 500-3000 lines/file. **All filenames must use snake_case.**\n973: \n974: **scripts/** (Optional): Python logic - procedural, routing, validation. Requires type hints, tests\n975: \n976: **assets/** (Optional): YAML configs, workflow definitions, templates, mappings\n977: \n978: **tests/** (Required if scripts/ exists): Unit tests with ≥80% coverage, pytest, `test_[name].py`\n979: \n980: ### When to Create Each Directory\n981: \n982: | Directory     | Create When                                                     | Don't Create When                           |\n983: | ------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------- |\n984: | `references/` | Content >200 lines, multi-phase workflows, systematic debugging | Simple skills <200 lines total              |\n985: | `scripts/`    | Python logic extracted from markdown, reusable functions        | Pure documentation, no executable logic     |\n986: | `assets/`     | YAML configs, templates, structured data                        | No configuration data, inline examples only |\n987: | `tests/`      | `scripts/` directory exists                                     | No Python scripts to test                   |\n988: \n989: ### Integration Pattern\n990: \n991: **How components work together:**\n992: - SKILL.md references scripts: `[workflow_router.py](./scripts/workflow_router.py)`\n993: - Scripts load configs: `yaml.safe_load(f\"../assets/config.yaml\")`\n994: - Tests verify scripts: `assert route_workflow(\"input\").mode == \"expected\"`\n995: - Markdown links to all: \"See [script.py](../scripts/), [config.yaml](../assets/)\"\n996: \n997: ---\n998: \n999: ## 9. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n1000: \n1001: ### Templates\n1002: - [frontmatter_templates.md](../frontmatter_templates.md) - Frontmatter by document type\n1003: - [skill_md_template.md](./skill_md_template.md) - If converting to skill\n1004: - [skill_asset_template.md](./skill_asset_template.md) - Asset file creation guide\n1005: \n1006: ### Standards\n1007: - [core_standards.md](../../references/global/core_standards.md) - Document type rules\n1008: - [skill_creation.md](../../references/skill_creation.md) - Complete skill creation workflow\n\n(End of file - total 1008 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Skill Reference File Templates\ndescription: Comprehensive templates for creating effective reference files for AI agent skills with workflows, decision logic, and validation checkpoints.\n---\n\n# Skill Reference File Templates - AI Agent Skills\n\nTemplates for creating reference files in AI agent skills with deep-dive technical guidance.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Location & Naming\n\n**Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/references/`\n\n**Naming Convention:** snake_case with `.md` extension only\n\n| ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md","time":{"start":1780204917165,"end":1780204917190}},"id":"prt_e7c7b5034001SWZMvySQ0Kq5dM","sessionID":"ses_18385aec7ffebZlYV7nY3fdUmq","messageID":"msg_e7c7b3054001i9VsPvsC4VPC8C"}}
